irus: 10 deaths, 300 hospitalisations linked to Tablighi Jamaat meet in Nizamuddin |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-10-deaths-300-hospitalisations-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-meet/articleshow/74902930.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=31 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that air quality index of Delhi improved on 28 March 2020 after the lockdown and reduced vehicular movements.<ref>{{citation |title=Corona blue: Clear skies, clean air in Delhi |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/delhi/corona-blue-clear-skies-clean-air/articleshow/74855039.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Delhi medical cases chart}}\n\n\n==Government responses==\n===March===\n\n====Travel and entry restrictions====\nChief minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] announced that from 23 to 31 March 2020, all domestic/international flights arriving to [[Delhi]] would be suspended.<ref name=\"EcoTimes23March\"/>\n\n===Lockdown===\n* '''22 March'''\n:*Arvind Kejriwal had announced [[lockdown]] from 23 March 6 a.m. to 31 March midnight. Except essential services every services had been closed due to [[COVID-19]] pandemic. Borders had been sealed except for transportation of essential services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus in Delhi: CM Kejriwal announces lockdown from March 23 to 31|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-in-delhi-cm-kejriwal-announces-lockdown-from-march-23-to-31/videoshow/74761871.cms|accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''24 March'''\n:*Lockdown further extended till 14 April 2020 after PM [[Narendra Modi]] announced a complete nationwide lockdown, starting from midnight of 24 March 2020 for 21 days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/narendra-modi-on-coronavirus-speech-live-updates-streaming-watch-india-pm-address-to-nation-on-covid-19-today-latest-news-lockdown-janata-curfew-8182241.html|title=Narendra Modi on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: India under complete shutdown for 21 days starting 12 pm tonight, says PM|date=|work=The Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*'''14 April'''\n:*Modi extended lockdown  till 3 May 2020. <ref name=\"lockdownext\">\n{{cite news |first1=Utpal|last1=Bhaskar|title=PM Modi announces extension of lockdown till 3 May | url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-announces-extension-of-lockdown-till-3-may-11586839412073.html |work=The Livemint |date=14 April 2020}}\n</ref>after recommendation from several state governments.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Rounak|last1=Jain|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/lockdown-in-telangana-extended-till-june-3/articleshow/75014509.cms|title=Telangana CM suggests lockdown extension by two weeks|date=|work=The Business Insder|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n===Commercial establishments===\nOn 19 March, Arvind Kejriwal announced that all restaurants will be closed till 31 March in view of the ever increasing case of coronavirus. He said that there will be a take away system from restaurants without any eating facilities in the venue. He also said that 20 or more people will not be allowed to unite anywhere in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kejriwal govt orders Delhi restaurants to shut shop with immediate effect until 31 March| url=https://theprint.in/india/kejriwal-govt-orders-delhi-restaurants-to-shut-shop-with-immediate-effect-until-31-march/384034/|website=theprint|author=}}</ref>\nAll shops, industries,  commercial establishments, offices  shall be closed.<ref name=\"EcoTimes23March\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Fallout: Delhi CM Arvind Kejriwal announces lockdown until March 31 |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-fallout-delhi-cm-arvind-kejriwal-announces-lockdown-until-march-31/articleshow/74761137.cms |accessdate=17 April 2020 |publisher=The Economic Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==State government response==\nDelhi government had initiated a disinfection drive in Delhi from 13 April 2020<ref>{{citation |title=Covid-19: Delhi govt to sanitise city's red, orange zones from Monday, says Arvind Kejriwal|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-delhi-govt-to-sanitise-city-s-red-orange-zones-from-monday-says-arvind-kejriwal-1666196-2020-04-12|work=[[India Today]] |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Delhi Govt disinfection drive during COVID-19 pandemic in DelhiVID 20200416 132044.webm|thumb|Delhi Govt disinfection drive during COVID-19 pandemic in Delhi]]\n=== Help ===\n\n====Ration====\n*'''4 April,''' as per CM [[Arvind Kejriwal|Arvind Kejriwal's]] announcement people who dont have ration card can avail free ration from fair price shop.<ref>{{citation|title=People-without-Ration-Cards-in-Delhi-can-now-avail-free-ration-from-Fair-Price-Shops|url=http://newsonair.com/News?title=People-without-Ration-Cards-in-Delhi-can-now-avail-free-ration-from-Fair-Price-Shops%3A-Delhi-govt&id=384700|work=News On Air|date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''5 April''',  out of 71 lakh ration card holder in Delhi 60% had received ration.<ref name=\"ration\">{{citation|title=Delhi: 60% of 71 lakh people under PDS given ration, those without cards can fill forms|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-60-of-71-lakh-people-under-pds-given-ration-those-without-cards-can-fill-forms-6347808/|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=5 April 2020}}</ref>. As per CM till 5 April 50,000 to 60,000 people hv applied for coupon to avail 5 kg of wheat, rice and sugar, free of cost and who don't have ration card.<ref  name=\"ration\"/> Some people complained about distribution, in a video conference with area MLAs including other party, CM requested that they should reach out to people in distress and help them register to avail ration.<ref  name=\"ration\"/>\n\n=== Hotspot ===\n[[File:Minister visiting the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre 2.jpg|thumb|The Minister of State for Home Affairs, [[Nityanand Rai]] visiting evacuees at the Coronavirus Quarantine Centre, after completion of their requisite quarantine period, at the ITBP Chhawla Centre, in New Delhi on 13 March 2020.]]\nOn 14 April 2020 after adding eight new hotspots, now total hotspot numbers are 55 in Delhi.<ref>{{citation |title=Coronavirus lockdown: 8 more hotspots in Delhi, 55 areas sealed in Delhi|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-lockdown-8-more-hotspots-in-delhi-55-areas-sealed-in-delhi-check-full-list-here-1667005-2020-04-14|work=[[India Today]]|date=14 April 2020 }}</ref> On 15 April 2020 after adding two more places, total hotspot numbers are 57.<ref name=15AprilIndiaToday>{{citation |title=Coronavirus: Delhi adds 2 areas in containment zone list, city tally rises to 1,578|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/complete-list-of-57-coronavirus-containment-zones-in-delhi-1667371-2020-04-15|work=[[India Today]]|date=15 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== SHIELD plan ===\nThe Delhi Government announced operation SHIELD in order to curb the spread of the virus in the containment zones or the hotspots. It is a six layers plan, where S refers to sealing the immediate area, H refers to home quarantine to all people living in the area, I refers to isolation and contact tracing of people, E refers to essential supply of commodities, L refers to local sanitization and D refers to door to door helth check of people in the area.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Delhi govt announces Operation SHIELD to take on COVID-19 |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/coronavirus-delhi-govt-announces-operation-shield-to-take-on-covid-19/story/400648.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=The Business Today |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The first success of the operation came from Dilshad Garden, an area where the virus was widely spreaded. The Dlehi Government annoucned on 10 April, that the operation SHIELD was successful in containing the spread of the virus in this area. The state Health Minister, [[Satyendra Kumar Jain|Satyendra Jain]] said that the area was virus-free after the implentation of the six layer operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Operation SHIELD successful in containing COVID-19 spread in Dilshad Garden: Delhi health minister |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/operation-shield-successful-in-containing-covid-19-spread-in-dilshad-garden-delhi-health-minister/articleshow/75082473.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cases ==\n=== Cases by districts ===\n{{updated|17 April 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Administrative district wise +ve cases<ref>{{cite web |title=State/District wise Details of COVID-19 positive cases |url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/pdf/Districtreporting408.pdf |publisher=Govt. of India (MoHFW) |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n! District !! Number of cases\n|-\n| Central Delhi || 75\n|-\n| East Delhi DELHI || 30\n|-\n| New Delhi || 26\n|-\n| North Delhi || 24\n|-\n| North-East Delhi || 15\n|-\n| North-West Delhi || 14\n|-\n| Shahadara  || 37\n|-\n| South Delhi || 62\n|-\n| South-East Delhi|| 65\n|-\n| South-West Delhi || 20\n|-\n| West Delhi || 49\n|-\n|  TJ from Quarantine  || 1080\n|-\n|  Others non traceable  || 143\n|-\n| TOTAL  || 1640\n|}\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by city|Delhi]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Delhi]]\n[[Category:2020s in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Health in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Delhi]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Delhi"}
{"title_page": "Western Ghats", "text_new": "{{short description|Mountain range along the western coast of India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Western Ghats\n| other_name =\n| photo=Western_Ghats_Gobi.jpg\n| photo_caption= The Western Ghats as seen from [[Gobichettipalayam]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| state= [[Gujarat]]\n| state1= [[Maharashtra]]\n| state2= [[Goa]]\n| state3= [[Karnataka]]\n| state4= [[Kerala]]\n| state5= [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| region= [[Western India]]\n| region1= [[Southern India]]\n| city1 = [[Surat]]\n| city2 = [[Mumbai]]\n| city3 = [[Pune]]\n| city4 = [[Kolhapur]]\n| city5 = [[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]]\n| city6 = [[Shivamogga]]\n| city7 = [[Chikkamagalur]]\n| city8 = [[Mangalore]]\n| city9 = [[Madikeri]]\n| city10 = [[Erode]]\n| city11 = [[Coimbatore]]\n| city12 = [[Kochi]]\n| city13 = [[Tenkasi]]\n| city14 = [[Tirunelveli]]\n| city15 = [[Thiruvananthapuram]]\n| geology = [[Basalt]]\n| geology1= [[Laterite]]\n| geology2 = [[Limestone]]\n| period = [[Cenozoic]]\n| biome = [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests]]\n<!-- *** Geography *** -->\n| area_km2= 160000\n| length_km= 1600\n| length_orientation= N\u2013S\n| width_km= 100\n| width_orientation= E\u2013W\n| highest= [[Anamudi]], [[Kerala]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|10|10|N|77|04|E|type:mountain|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| highest_location= [[Eravikulam National Park]]\n| elevation_m       = 2695\n| image_map=Satellite Picture of the Western Ghats & Indian West Coast.png\n| map_caption= The Western Ghats lie roughly parallel to the west coast of India.\n| embedded ={{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n| child = yes\n| ID = 1342\n| Year = 2012\n| Criteria = Natural: ix, x\n| Area = 795,315 ha\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Western Ghats''', also known as '''Sahyadri''' (Benevolent Mountains), are a mountain range that covers an area of {{convert|140000|km2}} in a stretch of {{convert|1600|km}} parallel to the western coast of the [[India]]n peninsula, traversing the states of [[Kerala]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Karnataka]], [[Goa]], [[Maharashtra]] and [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Western Ghats|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342}}</ref> It is a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] and is one of the eight \"hottest hot-spots\" of [[biological diversity]] in the world.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Biodiversity hotspots for conservation priorities|journal=Nature|volume=403|issue=6772|pages=853\u2013858|doi=10.1038/35002501|pmid=10706275|year=2000|last1=Myers|first1=Norman|last2=Mittermeier|first2=Russell A.|last3=Mittermeier|first3=Cristina G.|last4=Da Fonseca|first4=Gustavo A. B.|last5=Kent|first5=Jennifer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-02/flora-fauna/32507340_1_world-heritage-list-western-ghats-border-town|title=UN designates Western Ghats as world heritage site|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date=2 July 2012|access-date=2 July 2012}}</ref> It is sometimes called the Great [[Escarpment]] of India.<ref>{{cite book|last=Migon|first=Piotr|title=Geomorphological Landscapes of the World|date=12 May 2010|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-90-481-3054-2|page=257}}</ref> It contains a large proportion of the country's [[flora]] and [[fauna]], many of which are only found in India and nowhere else in the world.<ref>{{citation|title=A biodiversity hotspot|url=http://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/where_we_work/western_ghats/}}</ref> According to [[UNESCO]], the Western Ghats are older than the [[Himalayas]]. They influence Indian monsoon weather patterns by intercepting the rain-laden monsoon winds that sweep in from the south-west during late summer.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The range runs north to south along the western edge of the [[Deccan Plateau]], and separates the plateau from a narrow coastal plain, called [[Konkan]], along the [[Arabian Sea]]. A total of thirty-nine areas in the Western Ghats, including national parks, wildlife sanctuaries and reserve forests, were designated as world heritage sites in 2012 \u2013 twenty in [[Kerala]], ten in [[Karnataka]], five in [[Tamil Nadu]] and four in [[Maharashtra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342/multiple=1&unique_number=1921|title=Western Ghats|work=[[UNESCO]]|access-date=3 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Clara|last=Lewis|date=3 July 2012|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-03/mumbai/32523277_1_radhanagari-wildlife-world-heritage-centre-western-ghats|title=39 sites in Western Ghats get world heritage status |newspaper=[[Times of India]]|access-date=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe range starts near the [[Songadh]] town of [[Gujarat]], south of the [[Tapti river]], and runs approximately {{convert|1600|km|abbr=on}} through the states of [[Maharashtra]], [[Goa]], [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Tamil Nadu]] ending at [[Marunthuvazh Malai]], at [[Swamithope]], near the southern tip of India. These hills cover {{convert|160000|km2|abbr=on}} and form the catchment area for complex riverine [[Drainage system (geomorphology)|drainage systems]] that drain almost 40% of India. The Western Ghats block [[southwest monsoon]] winds from reaching the Deccan Plateau.{{cn|date=March 2020}} The average elevation is around {{convert|1200|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"APMN\">{{cite web|url=http://apmn.icimod.org/mountains/ch2_peninsula.php|title= The Peninsula|access-date=19 March 2007|work=Asia-Pacific Mountain Network |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070812064356/http://apmn.icimod.org/mountains/ch2_peninsula.php|archive-date=12 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe area is one of the world's ten \"hottest [[biodiversity hotspot]]s\" and has over 7,402 species of flowering plants, 1,814 species of non-flowering plants, 139 mammal species, 508 bird species, 179 amphibian species, 6,000 insects species and 290 freshwater fish species; it is likely that many undiscovered species live in the Western Ghats. At least 325 globally [[threatened species]] occur in the Western Ghats.<ref name=\"Flowering plants\">{{cite book |last1=Nayar |first1=T.S. |last2=Rasiya Beegam |first2=A |last3=Sibi |first3=M. |title=Flowering Plants of the Western Ghats, India (2 Volumes) |date=2014 |publisher=Jawaharlal Nehru Tropical Botanic Garden and Research Institute. p.1700|location=Thiruvananthapuram, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Myers |first1=N. |last2=Mittermeier |first2=R.A. |last3=Mittermeier |first3=C.G. |last4=Fonseca |first4=G.A.B.Da |last5=Kent |first5=J. |year=2000 |title=Biodiversity Hotspots for Conservation Priorities |journal=Nature |volume=403 |issue=6772 |pages=853\u2013858 |doi=10.1038/35002501 |pmid=10706275}}</ref><ref name=\"Neelesh Fish\">{{cite journal |last1=Dahanukar |first1=N. |last2=Raut |first2=R. |last3=Bhat |first3=A. |year=2004 |title=Distribution, endemism and threat status of freshwater fishes in the Western Ghats of India |journal=Journal of Biogeography |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=123\u2013136 |doi=10.1046/j.0305-0270.2003.01016.x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5c915245a382eabc0650d1e37492c57e6c59e70e }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word [[ghat]] is explained by numerous [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] etymons such as [[Tamil language|Tamil]] gattu (hill and hill forest), [[Kannada language|Kannada]] ''gaati'' and ''ghatta'' (mountain range), [[Tulu language|Tulu]] ''gatta'' (hill or hillside),  and ''ghattam'' in [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] (mountainous way, riverside and hairpin bends).<ref>{{cite book|last=Jaini|first=Padmanabh S.|title=Jainism and Early Buddhism|year=2003|publisher=Jain Publishing Company|pages=523\u2013538|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5_EdL2FtIqQC&dq=etymology+dravidian|isbn=9780895819567}}</ref>\n\n''Ghat'', a term used in the [[Indian subcontinent]], depending on the context could either refer to a [[Geography of India#Coastal plains and ghats|range of stepped-hill]] such as the [[Eastern Ghats]] and Western Ghats; or the series of steps leading down to a body of water or [[wharf]], such bathing or cremation place along the banks of a river or pond, [[Ghats in Varanasi]], [[Dhoby Ghaut]] or [[Aapravasi Ghat]].<ref name=dict1>Sunithi L. Narayan, Revathy Nagaswami, 1992, [https://books.google.com/books?id=miZuAAAAMAAJ&q=ghat+means&dq=ghat+means&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_nZnwjpPgAhUHWysKHQcdAjk4ChDoAQgpMAA Discover sublime India: handbook for tourists], Page 5.</ref><ref name=dict2>[https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/ghat Ghat definition], Cambridge dictionary.</ref> Roads passing through ghats are called [[Ghat Roads]].\n\n==Geology==\nThe Western Ghats are the mountainous [[Fault (geology)|faulted]] and [[Erosion|eroded]] edge of the [[Deccan Plateau]]. Geologic evidence indicates that they were formed during the break-up of the supercontinent of [[Gondwana]] some 150 million years ago. [[geophysics|Geophysical]] evidence indicates that the west coast of India came into being somewhere around 100 to 80 [[mya (unit)|mya]] after it broke away from [[Madagascar]]. After the break-up, the western coast of India would have appeared as an abrupt cliff some {{convert|1000|m|abbr=on}} in [[elevation]].<ref name=\"Barron, E.J.\">{{cite journal |last1=Barron |first1=E.J. |last2=Harrison |first2= C.G.A. |last3=Sloan |first3=J.L. II |last4=Hay |first4=W.W. |year=1981 |title= Paleogeography, 180 million years ago to the present |journal=Eclogae Geologicae Helvetiae |volume=74 |issue=2 |pages=443\u2013470}}</ref> [[Basalt]] is the predominant rock found in the hills reaching a thickness of {{convert|3|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}. Other rock types found are [[charnockite]]s, [[granite]] gneiss, [[khondalite]]s, [[leptynite]]s, metamorphic [[gneiss]]es with detached occurrences of crystalline [[limestone]], iron ore, [[dolerite]]s and [[anorthosite]]s. Residual [[laterite]] and [[bauxite]] ores are also found in the southern hills.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Tamil Nadu topo deutsch mit Gebirgen.png|thumb|Topography: Western Ghats (southern part)]]\nThe Western Ghats extend from the [[Satpura Range]] in the north, stretching from [[Gujarat]] to [[Tamil Nadu]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} It traverses south through the states of [[Maharashtra]], [[Goa]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Kerala]]. Major gaps in the range are the [[Goa Gap]], between the Maharashtra and Karnataka sections, and the [[Palghat Gap]] on the Tamil Nadu and Kerala border between the Nilgiri Hills and the [[Anaimalai Hills]]. The mountains intercept the rain-bearing westerly [[monsoon]] winds, and are consequently an area of high rainfall, particularly on their western side. The dense forests also contribute to the precipitation of the area by acting as a substrate for condensation of moist rising [[orographic]] winds from the sea, and releasing much of the moisture back into the air via [[transpiration]], allowing it to later condense and fall again as rain.\n\nThe northern portion of the narrow coastal plain between the Western Ghats and the [[Arabian Sea]] is known as the [[Konkan Coast|Konkan]], the central portion is called [[Kanara]] and the southern portion is called [[Malabar Coast|Malabar]]. The foothill region east of the Ghats in [[Maharashtra]] is known as [[Desh, Maharashtra|Desh]], while the eastern foothills of the central Karnataka state is known as [[Malenadu]].<ref name=\"all-about-india.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.all-about-india.com/Geography-of-India.html|title=The Geography of India|publisher=all-about-india.com|access-date=19 November 2010}}</ref> The range is known as ''Sahyadri'' in [[Maharashtra]] and [[Karnataka]]. The Western Ghats meet the [[Eastern Ghats]] at the [[Nilgiri mountains]] in northwestern [[Tamil Nadu]]. The Nilgiris connect the [[Biligiriranga Hills]] in southeastern Karnataka with the [[Shevaroys]] and [[Tirumala]] hills. South of the [[Palghat Gap]] are the [[Anamala Hills]], located in western Tamil Nadu and Kerala with smaller ranges further south, including the [[Cardamom Hills]], then [[Aryankavu]] pass, and [[Aralvaimozhi]] pass near Kanyakumari. The range is known as ''Sahyan'' or ''Sahian'' in [[Kerala]]. In the southern part of the range is [[Anamudi]] ({{convert|2695|m|ft|0}}), the highest peak in the Western Ghats.\n\n===Peaks===\n{{Main|List of peaks in the Western Ghats}}\nThe Western Ghats have many peaks that rise above 2,000 meters, with [[Anamudi]] ({{convert|2695|m|ft|abbr=on}}) being the highest peak.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Water bodies===\n[[File:Varandha ghad.jpg|thumb|View from Varandha Pass Mahad showing the numerous waterfalls]]\nThe Western Ghats form one of the four [[Drainage basin|watersheds]] of India, feeding the perennial rivers of India. The major river systems originating in the Western Ghats are the [[Godavari river|Godavari]], [[Kaveri river|Kaveri]], [[Krishna river|Krishna]], [[Thamiraparani]] and [[Tungabhadra]] rivers. The majority of streams draining the Western Ghats join these rivers, and carry a large volume of water during the monsoon months. These rivers flow to the east due to the gradient of the land and drain out into the [[Bay of Bengal]]. Major tributaries include the [[Kali River (Karnataka)|Kali]], [[Bhadra river|Bhadra]], [[Bhavani river|Bhavani]], [[Bhima River|Bhima]], [[Malaprabha River|Malaprabha]], [[Ghataprabha River|Ghataprabha]], [[Hemavathi river|Hemavathi]] and [[Kabini River|Kabini]] rivers. The [[Periyar River|Periyar]], [[Bharathappuzha]], [[Pamba River|Pamba]], [[Netravati River|Netravati]], [[Sharavathi]], [[Mandovi]] and [[Zuari River|Zuari]] rivers flow westwards towards the Western Ghats, draining into the [[Arabian Sea]], and are fast-moving, owing to the steeper gradient.\n\n[[File:Jog Falls, India - August 2006.jpg|thumb|left|[[Jog Falls]] in Karnataka, one of the most spectacular waterfalls in India]]\nThe rivers have been dammed for [[hydroelectric]] and [[irrigation]] purposes with major reservoirs spread across the states. The reservoirs are important for their commercial and sport fisheries of [[rainbow trout]], [[mahseer]] and [[common carp]].<ref name=SehgalFish>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/003/x2614e/x2614e06.htm|last=Sehgal|first=K. L.|title= Coldwater fish and fisheries in the Western Ghats, India|publisher=[[FAO]]|access-date=22 September 2008}}</ref> There are about 50 major dams along the length of the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/resources/statistics/stat233.htm|title=Indian Dams by River and State|publisher=Rain water harvesting|access-date=19 March 2007}}</ref> Most notable of these projects are the [[Koyna Hydroelectric Project|Koyna]] in Maharashtra, [[Linganmakki Dam|Linganmakki]] and [[Shivanasamudra]] in Karnataka, [[Mettur Dam|Mettur]] and [[Pykara]] in Tamil Nadu, [[Parambikulam Dam|Parambikulam]], [[Malampuzha Dam|Malampuzha]] and [[Idukki dam|Idukki]] in Kerala.<ref name=\"all-about-india.com\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Rajesh|last=Menon|url=http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=151253|title=Tremors may rock Koyna for another two-decade|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|date=3 October 2005|access-date=19 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117083928/http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=151253|archive-date=17 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first1=R.L.|last1=Samani|first2=A.P.|last2=Ayhad|title=Silting Problems in Hydropower Plants|editor=S. P. Kaushish|editor2=B. S. K. Naidu|publisher=Central Board of Irrigation and Power|location=Bangkok|year=2002|chapter=Siltation of Reservoirs-Koyna Hydroelectric Project-A Case Study|isbn=978-90-5809-238-0}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Banasura sagar.jpg|thumb|right|[[Banasura Sagar Dam]]]]\nDuring the monsoon season, numerous streams fed by incessant rain drain off the mountain sides leading to numerous waterfalls. Major waterfalls include [[Dudhsagar Falls|Dudhsagar]], [[Unchalli Falls|Unchalli]],\n[[Sathodi Falls|Sathodi]], [[Magod Falls|Magod]], [[Hogenakkal Falls|Hogenakkal]], [[Jog Falls|Jog]], [[Kunchikal Falls|Kunchikal]], [[Shivanasamudra Falls|Shivanasamudra]], [[Meenmutty Falls, Wayanad|Meenmutty Falls]], [[Athirappilly Falls]]. [[Talakaveri]] is the source of the river Kaveri and the Kuduremukha range is the source of the Tungabhadra. The Western Ghats have several man-made lakes and reservoirs with major lakes at [[Ooty Lake|Ooty]] ({{convert|34|ha}}) in Nilgiris, [[Kodaikanal Lake|Kodaikanal]] ({{convert|26|ha}}) and [[Berijam Lake|Berijam]] in [[Palani Hills]], [[Pookode lake]], Karlad Lake in [[Wayanad]], [[Vagamon]] lake, [[Devikulam]] ({{convert|6|ha}}) and Letchmi ({{convert|2|ha}}) in [[Idukki]], Kerala.\n[[File:Chembra Peak seen from Pookode Lake.JPG|thumb|Chembra Peak seen from Pookode Lake]]\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Western-Ghats-rainfall.svg|thumb|upright|Annual rainfall along the Western Ghat region]]\nThe area including [[Agumbe]], [[Hulikal]] and [[Amagaon]] in [[Karnataka]], Mahabaleshwar and Tamhini in [[Maharashtra]] are often referred to as the \"[[Cherrapunji]] of southwest India\" or the \"rain capital of southwest India\". [[Kollur, Udupi district|Kollur in Udupi district]], Kokkali and [[Nilkund]] in [[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Samse]] in [[Mudigere]] of [[Karnataka]], and [[Neriamangalam]] in the [[Ernakulam district]] of [[Kerala]] are the wettest places in the Western Ghats. Heavy precipitation does occur in the surrounding regions due to the long continuity of the mountains without passes and gaps. Changes in the direction and pace of the wind do affect the average rainfall and the wettest places might vary. However, [[Maharashtra]] and the northern part of Western Ghats in [[Karnataka]] on average receive heavier rainfall than [[Kerala]] and the southern part of Western Ghats in Karnataka.\n\nThe climate in the Western Ghats varies with altitudinal gradation and distance from the equator. The climate is humid and tropical in the lower reaches tempered by the proximity to the sea. Elevations of {{convert|1500|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} and above in the north and {{convert|2000|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} and above in the south have a more temperate climate. The average annual temperature is around {{convert|15|\u00b0C}}. In some parts frost is common, and temperatures reach the freezing point during the winter months. Mean temperatures range from {{convert|20|\u00b0C}} in the south to {{convert|24|\u00b0C}} in the north. It has also been observed that the coldest periods in the South Western Ghats coincide with the wettest.<ref name=\"WII\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter2.htm|first=R.J.|last=Ranjit Daniels|title=Biodiversity of the Western Ghats \u2013 An Overview|access-date=19 March 2007|work=Wildlife Institute of India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070228195706/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter2.htm|archivedate=28 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[monsoon|monsoon season]] between June and September, the unbroken Western Ghats chain acts as a barrier to the moisture-laden clouds. The heavy, eastward-moving rain-bearing clouds are forced to rise and in the process deposit most of their rain on the windward side. Rainfall in this region averages {{convert|300|cm}} to {{convert|400|cm}} with localised extremes reaching {{convert|900|cm}}. The eastern regions of the Western Ghats, which lie in the [[rain shadow]], receive far less rainfall (about {{convert|100|cm}}), resulting in an average rainfall of {{convert|250|cm}} across all regions. The total amount of rain does not depend on the spread of the area; areas in northern Maharashtra receive heavy rainfall followed by long dry spells, while regions closer to the equator receive less annual rainfall and have rain spells lasting several months in a year.<ref name=\"WII\"/>\n\n===Rainfall===\nThe Karnataka region on average receives heavier rainfall than the Kerala, Maharashtra and Goa. Meanwhile, the Ghats in Karnataka have fewer passes and gaps and therefore the western slopes of Karnataka receive heavy rainfall, over 400&nbsp;cm more than other regional parts of the Western Ghats.\n\nSome of the wettest places in the Western Ghats are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Region\n!Mean annual rainfall<ref>https://en.climate-data.org</ref>\n|-\n|[[Agumbe]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Thirthahalli|[[Thirthahalli]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|7624|{{convert|7624|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Amboli, Sindhudurg|Amboli]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Sindhudurg|[[Sindhudurg district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|3859|{{convert|3859|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Hulikal]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Hosanagara|[[Hosanagara]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|5316|{{convert|5316|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Amagaon]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Khanapur|[[Khanapur]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4089|{{convert|4089|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Kakkali|Kakkalli]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada, Sirsi|[[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4921|{{convert|4921|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Nilkund]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada, Sirsi|[[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4369|{{convert|4369|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Mahabaleshwar]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Satara|[[Satara district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|5761|{{convert|5761|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Devimane Ghat|Devimane]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada, Sirsi|[[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|3981|{{convert|3981|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Surli]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Hosanagara|[[Hosanagara]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4335|{{convert|4335|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Lonavla]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Pune|[[Pune district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|4073|{{convert|4073|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Charmadi]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Mudigere|[[Mudigere]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4131|{{convert|4131|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Samse]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Mudigere|[[Mudigere]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|3914|{{convert|3914|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Kollur, Udupi district|Kollur]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Udupi|[[Udupi district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4992|{{convert|4992|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Makkiyad]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Wayanad|[[Wayanad district]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|3714|{{convert|3714|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Kudremukh]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Chikmagalur|[[Chikmagalur district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4158|{{convert|4158|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Rajamalai]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Idukki|[[Idukki]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|4785|{{convert|4785|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Nyamakad]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Idukki|[[Idukki]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|3007|{{convert|3007|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Sholayar]]\n|{{sort|Tamil Nadu, Coimbatore|[[Coimbatore]], [[Tamil Nadu]]}}\n|{{sort|3024|{{convert|3024|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Vythiri]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Wayanad|[[Wayanad district]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|4000|{{convert|4000|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Pookode]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Wayanad|[[Wayanad district]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|3957|{{convert|3957|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Dhamanohol]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Mulshi taluka|[[Mulshi taluka]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|6255|{{convert|6255|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Mulshi]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Pune|[[Pune district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|5100|{{convert|5100|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Tamhini Ghat]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Mulshi taluka|[[Mulshi taluka]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|5255|{{convert|5255|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Chinnakallar Falls|Chinnakallar]]\n|{{sort|Tamil Nadu, Coimbatore|[[Coimbatore]], [[Tamil Nadu]]}}\n|{{sort|2947|{{convert|2947|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Castle Rock, Karnataka|Castle Rock]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada|[[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|5132|{{convert|5132|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|}\n\n==Ecoregions==\n[[File:Shola.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sholas]], part of the rainforests]]\nThe Western Ghats are home to four [[tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forest]] [[ecoregions]] \u2013 the [[North Western Ghats moist deciduous forests]], [[North Western Ghats montane rain forests]], [[South Western Ghats moist deciduous forests]], and [[South Western Ghats montane rain forests]]. The northern portion of the range is generally drier than the southern portion, and at lower elevations makes up the North Western Ghats moist deciduous forests ecoregion, with mostly deciduous forests made up predominantly of [[teak]]. Above 1,000 meters elevation are the cooler and wetter [[North Western Ghats montane rain forests]], whose evergreen forests are characterised by trees of the family ''[[Lauraceae]]''.\n\nThe evergreen forests in [[Wayanad]] mark the transition zone between the northern and southern ecoregions of the Western Ghats. The southern ecoregions are generally wetter and more species-rich. At lower elevations are the [[South Western Ghats moist deciduous forests]], with ''[[Cullenia]]'' the characteristic tree genus, accompanied by teak, [[dipterocarp]]s, and other trees. The moist forests transition to the drier [[South Deccan Plateau dry deciduous forests]], which lie in its rain shadow to the east. Above 1,000 meters are the [[South Western Ghats montane rain forests]], also cooler and wetter than the surrounding lowland forests, and dominated by evergreen trees, although some [[montane grassland]]s and stunted forests can be found at the highest elevations. The South Western Ghats montane rain forests are the most species-rich ecoregion in peninsular India; eighty percent of the [[flowering plant]] species of the entire Western Ghats range are found in this ecoregion.\n\n==Biodiversity protection==\n[[File:Western ghaats1, maharashtra.jpg|thumb|Dense rainforests cover the Western Ghats.]]\n[[File:Heavenly Sahyadri.jpg|thumb|The Western Ghats are a UNESCO heritage site.]]\nHistorically the Western Ghats were covered in dense forests that provided wild foods and natural habitats for native [[Indigenous peoples|tribal people]]. Its inaccessibility made it difficult for people from the [[Deccan Plateau|plains]] to cultivate the land and build settlements. After the arrival of the [[British empire#Expansion|British]] in the area, large swathes of territory were cleared for agricultural plantations and timber. The forest in the Western Ghats has been severely fragmented due to human activities, especially [[clear-felling]] for tea, coffee, and teak plantations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.manoramaonline.com/travel/beyond-kerala/2019/06/11/camp-worlds-highest-tea-estate-kolukkumalai-munnat-drive.html|title=Camp at world's highest tea estate Kolukkumalai|website=OnManorama|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> from 1860 to 1950.  Species that are rare, [[Endemism|endemic]] and habitat specialists are more adversely affected and tend to be lost faster than other species. Complex and species rich habitats like the tropical rainforest are much more adversely affected than other habitats.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2002/frag.wii.report.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20081219184202/http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2002/frag.wii.report.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 December 2008|title=Impact of rainforest fragmentation on small mammals and herpetofauna in the Western Ghats, South India|first=Ajith|last=Kumar|publisher=Salim Centre for Ornithology and Natural History, Coimbatore}}</ref>\n\nThe area is ecologically sensitive to development and was declared an ecological hotspot in 1988 through the efforts of ecologist [[Norman Myers]]. The area covers five percent of India's land; 27% of all species of higher plants in India (4,000 of 15,000 species) are found here and 1,800 of these are endemic to the region. The range is home to at least 84 amphibian species, 16 bird species, seven mammals, and 1,600 flowering plants which are not found elsewhere in the world. The [[Government of India]] has established many [[protected areas of India|protected areas]] including 2 [[Biosphere reserves of India|biosphere reserves]], 13 [[national parks of India|national parks]] to restrict human access, several [[Wildlife sanctuaries of India|wildlife sanctuaries]] to protect specific endangered species and many [[Reserved forests and protected forests of India|reserve forests]], which are all managed by the forest departments of their respective state to preserve some of the ecoregions still undeveloped. The [[Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve]], comprising {{convert|5500|km2}} of the evergreen forests of [[Nagarahole]] and deciduous forests of [[Bandipur National Park|Bandipur]] in Karnataka, adjoining regions of [[Wayanad]]-[[Mukurthi National Park|Mukurthi]] in Kerala and [[Mudumalai National Park]]-[[Sathyamangalam Wildlife Sanctuary|Sathyamangalam]] in Tamil Nadu, forms the largest contiguous protected area in the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cpreec.org/04_phamplets/08_nilgiri_bio_reser/nilgiri_bio_reser.html|title= The Nilgiri Bio-sphere Reserve|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928151229/http://www.cpreec.org/04_phamplets/08_nilgiri_bio_reser/nilgiri_bio_reser.html |archive-date=28 September 2006}}</ref> [[Silent Valley National Park|Silent Valley]] in Kerala is among the last tracts of virgin tropical evergreen forest in India.<ref name=\"wg\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/article52465.ece|title=No clearance for mining, hydel projects that destroy Western Ghat|last=Ramesh|date=21 November 2009|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|publisher=Kasturi & Sons Ltd.|access-date=29 December 2009|location=Palakkad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/08/04/stories/2009080456210300.htm|title=Gundia project has not got Centre's nod|last=staff|work=The Hindu |publisher=Kasturi & Sons Ltd.|access-date=29 December 2009|location=Chennai, India|date=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, the Western Ghats Ecology Expert Panel (WGEEP) designated the entire Western Ghats as an Ecologically Sensitive Area (ESA) and assigned three levels of Ecological Sensitivity to its different regions.<ref name=\"WGEP\">{{cite journal|url=http://moef.nic.in/downloads/public-information/wg-23052012.pdf|title=Report of the Western Ghats Ecology Expert Panel|author= Madhav Gadgil|publisher= Ministry of Environment and Forests, Government of India|date=2012-08-31|access-date=4 May 2012|website= Westernghatindia.org|volume=Part 1|pages= summary XIX}}</ref> The panel, headed by ecologist [[Madhav Gadgil]], was appointed by the Union [[Ministry of Environment and Forests]] to assess the biodiversity and environmental issues of the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/395071/vested-interests-harm-western-ghats.html|title=Vested interests in Western Ghats|newspaper=[[Deccan Herald]]|access-date=5 May 2016}}</ref> The [[Gadgil Committee]] and its successor, the Kasturirangan Committee, recommended suggestions to protect the Western Ghats. The Gadgil report was criticised as being too environment-friendly and the Kasturirangan report was labelled as being anti-environmental.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/kasturirangan-report-is-antienvironmental/article5533619.ece|title=Report is anti environmental|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/interview/the-kasturirangan-report-is-a-disaster-for-the-western-ghats/20131230.htm|title=Disaster for Western Ghats}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/paradise-lost/article1-1179300.aspx|title=Paradise lost|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|access-date=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, India applied to the [[UNESCO]] [[Man and the Biosphere Programme]] (MAB) for the Western Ghats to be listed as a protected [[List of World Heritage Sites in India|World Heritage Site]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|year=2007|title=World Heritage sites, Tentative lists, Western Ghats sub cluster|access-date=30 March 2007|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2103/}}</ref> In 2012, the following places were declared as World Heritage Sites:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342/multiple=1&unique_number=1921|title=UNESCO heritage sites|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|access-date=30 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/flora-fauna/UN-designates-Western-Ghats-as-world-heritage-site/articleshow/14595602.cms |title=UN designates Western Ghats as world heritage site|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date=2 July 2012|access-date=28 July 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n* [[Kali Tiger Reserve]], [[Dandeli]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Indira Gandhi Wildlife Sanctuary and National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* Mundigekere Bird Sanctuary, [[Sirsi, Karnataka]]\n* [[Kalakkad Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Thattekad Bird Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Shendurney Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Neyyar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Peppara Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Periyar Tiger Reserve]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Srivilliputtur Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Eravikulam National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Grass Hills National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Kerala]]\n* [[Karian Shola National Park]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Sathyamangalam Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Silent Valley National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Mukurthi National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Pushpagiri Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Brahmagiri Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* Mookambika Wildlife Sanctuary\n* [[Talakaveri Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Aralam Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Kudremukh National Park]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Someshwara Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Kaas Plateau]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Bhimashankar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Koyna Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Chandoli National Park]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Parambikulam Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Pambadum Shola National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Anamudi Shola National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Chimmony Wildlife Sanctuary]]\n* [[Peechi-Vazhani Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Mathikettan Shola National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Karimpuzha National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* Idukki Wildlife Sanctuary\n* Ranipuram National Park\n* [[Megamalai Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Palani Hills Wildlife Sanctuary and National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Kanyakumari Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Bandipur National Park]] [[Megamalai Wildlife Sanctuary|,]] [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Nagarhole National Park]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Fauna==\nThe Western Ghats are home to thousands of animal species including at least 325 globally [[threatened species]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mammals of the Western Ghats: A Simplistic Overview|first1=P.O.|last1=Nameer|first2=Sanjay|last2=Molur|first3=Sally|last3=Walker|date=November 2001|journal=Zoos' Print Journal|volume=16|issue=11|pages=629\u2013639|doi=10.11609/jott.zpj.16.11.629-39|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a782a69ce9472a58528e2cfbb98e13be3483f992}}</ref>\n\n===Mammals===\nThere are at least 139 [[mammal]] species. Of the 16 endemic mammals, 13 are threatened. Among the 32 threatened species are the [[critically endangered]] [[Malabar large-spotted civet]], the [[endangered]] [[lion-tailed macaque]], [[Nilgiri tahr]], [[Bengal tiger]] and [[Indian elephant]]s, the [[vulnerable species|vulnerable]] [[Indian leopard]], [[Nilgiri langur]] and [[gaur]].<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Participants of CBSG CAMP workshop: Status of South Asian Primates (March 2002)|year=2004|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/12559/0|title=''Macaca silenus''|access-date=9 May 2006|ref=harv}} Database entry includes justification for why this species is endangered</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mewa|first1=Singh|last2=Werner|first2=Kaumanns|year=2005|title=Behavioural studies: A necessity for wildlife management|url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/oct102005/1230.pdf|journal=Current Science|volume=89|issue=7|page=1233|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070113063948/http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/oct102005/1230.pdf|archivedate=13 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Malviya|first1=M.|last2=Srivastav|first2=A.|last3=Nigam|first3=P.|last4=Tyagi|first4=P.C.|title=Indian National Studbook of Nilgiri Langur (''Trachypithecus johnii'')|url=http://www.cza.nic.in/Nilgiri%20Langur%20studbook.pdf|year=2011|publisher=[[Wildlife Institute of India]], Dehradun and [[Central Zoo Authority]], New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nThese hill ranges serve as important [[wildlife corridor]]s and form an important part of [[Project Elephant]] and [[Project Tiger]] reserves. The largest population of tigers outside the [[Sundarban]]s is in the Western Ghats, where there are seven populations with an estimated population size of 336 to 487 individuals occupying {{convert|21435|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} of forest in three major landscape units spread across Karnataka, Tamil Nadu and Kerala.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Status of the Tigers, co-predators, and Prey in India|last1=Jhala|first1=Y. V.|last2=Gopal|first2=R.|last3=Qureshi|first3=Q|publisher=National Tiger Conservation Authority, Govt. of India, New Delhi; Wildlife Institute of India, Dehradun|year=2008|series=TR 08/001|url=http://projecttiger.nic.in/whtsnew/status_of_tigers_in_india_2008.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602124630/http://projecttiger.nic.in/whtsnew/status_of_tigers_in_india_2008.pdf|archivedate=2 June 2013}}</ref> The Western Ghats ecoregion has the largest Indian elephant population in the wild with an estimated 11,000 individuals across eight distinct populations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiienvis.nic.in/Database/eri_8226.aspx|title= Elephant Reserves|publisher=ENVIS Centre on Wildlife & Protected Areas|access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://envfor.nic.in/pe/PE%20Note.pdf|title=Census population 2005|year=2007|work=Note on Project Elephant|publisher=Ministry of Environment and Forests|access-date=30 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312060920/http://envfor.nic.in/pe/PE%20Note.pdf|archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref> The endemic [[Nilgiri tahr]], which was on the brink of extinction, has recovered and has an estimated 3,122 individuals in the wild.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/nilgiri-tahr-population-over-3000-wwfindia/article7717561.ece|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|title=Nilgiri tahr population over 3,000: WWF-India|date=3 October 2015|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> The [[critically endangered]] endemic [[Malabar large-spotted civet]] is estimated to number fewer than 250 mature individuals, with no sub-population greater than 50 individuals.<ref>{{cite iucn|author=Jennings, A.|author2=Veron, G.|author3=Helgen, K.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/23036/0|title=Viverra civettina|ref=harv}}</ref> About 3500 [[lion-tailed macaque]]s live scattered over several areas in the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Molur S|author2=D Brandon-Jones|author3=W Dittus|author4= A. Eudey|author5=A. Kumar|author6= M. Singh|author7=M.M. Feeroz|author8=M. Chalise|author9=P. Priya|author10=S. Walker|last-author-amp=yes|year=2003|title=Status of South Asian Primates: Conservation Assessment and Management Plan (C.A.M.P.) Workshop Report, 2003|publisher=Zoo Outreach Organization/CBSG-South Asia, Coimbatore}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Bengal_Tiger_Karnataka.jpg|The Western Ghats have the largest [[Bengal tiger|tiger]] population outside [[Sunderbans]].\nFile:Lightmatter lion-tailed macaque.jpg|The endangered [[lion-tailed macaque]] is endemic to the Western Ghats.\nFile:Elephas maximus (Bandipur).jpg|The Western Ghats region has the largest [[Indian elephant]] population in India.\nFile:Nilgiritragus_hylocrius.JPG|Only 100 individuals of [[Nilgiri tahr]] were left in 2001 but recovered to 3,300 by 2010.\nFile:Nilgiri langur (1) by N. A. Naseer.jpg|The endemic [[Nilgiri langur]] is endangered.\n</gallery>\n\n===Reptiles===\nThe major population of the snake family [[Uropeltidae]] is restricted to the region.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Greene, H. W.  |author2=R. W. Mcdiarmid |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2005|title=Wallace and Savage: heroes, theories and venomous snake mimicry, Ecology and Evolution in the Tropics, a Herpetological Perspective|pages=190\u2013208|publisher=Chicago University of Chicago Press}}</ref> Several endemic reptile genera occur here, including the cane turtle [[Vijayachelys silvatica]], lizards like [[Salea]], [[Ristella]], [[Kaestlea]], snakes like [[Melanophidium]], [[Plectrurus]], [[Teretrurus]], [[Platyplectrurus]], [[Xylophis]], [[Rhabdops]] and so on. Species-level [[endemism]] is much higher and is common to almost all genera present here. Some enigmatic endemic reptiles include the venomous snakes such as the striped coral snake, the [[Malabar pit viper]], the [[large-scaled pitviper]] and the [[horseshoe pitviper]]. The region has a significant population of the vulnerable [[mugger crocodile]].<ref>{{citation|first=Andrews|last=Harry V.|title=Status and Distribution of the Mugger Crocodile in Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/crocodile/tnadu.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20041220055759/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/crocodile/tnadu.htm|archivedate=20 December 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Amphibians===\nThe [[amphibian]]s of the Western Ghats are diverse and unique, with more than 80% of the 179 amphibian species being endemic to the [[Tropical rainforests of India|rainforests]] of the mountains.<ref>{{citation|author=Vasudevan Karthikeyan|title=A Report on the Survey of Rainforest Fragments in the Western Ghats for Amphibian Diversity|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter19.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20051215224533/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter19.htm|archivedate=15 December 2005}}</ref> The endangered [[purple frog]] was discovered in 2003.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Radhakrishnan, C |author2=K.C. Gopi |author3=K.P. Dinesh  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2007| title=Zoogeography of ''Nasikabatrachus sahyadrensis'' Biju and Bossuyt (Amphibia: Anura; Nasikabatrachidae) in the Western Ghats, India|journal=Records of the Zoological Survey of India|volume=107|pages= 115\u2013121}}</ref> Several families of frogs, namely of the genera [[Micrixalus]], [[Indirana]], [[Nyctibatrachus]], are endemic to this region. Endemic genera include the toads [[Pedostibes]], [[Ghatophryne]], [[Xanthophryne]]; arboreal frogs such as [[Ghatixalus]], [[Mercurana]] and [[Beddomixalus]]; and microhylids like [[Melanobatrachus]]. New frog species were described from the Western Ghats in 2005, and more recently a new species, [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic]] of its genus [[Mysticellus]], was discovered.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2005/endemism_amphibian_summary_content.pdf|title=An evaluation of the endemism of the amphibian assemblages from the Western Ghats using molecular techniques|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219184326/http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2005/endemism_amphibian_summary_content.pdf|archivedate=19 December 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCmonotypic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-47208169|title=New 'mysterious' frog species discovered in India's Western Ghats|date=13 February 2019|work=BBC News}}</ref>\nThe region is also home to many [[Caecilians of the Western Ghats|caecilian species]].\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Marsh Crocodiles basking in the sun.JPG|The region has a significant population of the vulnerable [[mugger crocodile]].\nFile:Nasikabatrachus_sahyadrensis.jpg|The [[purple frog]] (''Nasikabatrachus sahyadrensis'') was discovered in 2003.\nFile:Rhacophorus_malabaricus_flat.jpg|The [[Rhacophorus|Malabar gliding frog]] is endemic to the Western Ghats.\nFile:Plectrurus_perottetti_sal.jpg|[[Uropeltidae|Pipe snakes]] are found only in South India and Sri Lanka.\nFile:Akwa18 puntius2.jpg|[[Denison's barb]] is threatened from habitat loss and is now bred in captivity.\n</gallery>\n\n===Fish===\n{{as of|2004}}, 288 freshwater fish species were listed for the Western Ghats, including 35 also known from [[brackish]] or marine water.<ref name=\"Neelesh Fish\"/> Several new species have been described from the region since then (e.g., ''[[Dario urops]]'' and ''[[Schistura sharavathiensis|S. sharavathiensis]]'').<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Britz|last2=Ali|last3=Philip|year=2012|title=Dariourops, a new species of badid fish from the Western Ghats, southern India|journal=Zootaxa|volume=3348|pages=63\u201368|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3348.1.5}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sreekantha|last2=Gururaja|last3=Remadevi|last4=Indra|last5=Ramachandra|year=2006|title=Two new species of the genus Schistura McClell and (Cypriniformes: Balitoridae) from western Ghats, India|journal=Zoos' Print Journal|volume=21|issue=4|pages=2211\u20132216|doi=10.11609/jott.zpj.1386.2211-6|doi-access=free}}</ref> There are 118 endemic species, including 13 genera entirely restricted to the Western Ghats (''[[Betadevario]]'', ''[[Day's round herring|Dayella]]'', ''[[Haludaria]]'', ''[[Horabagrus]]'', ''[[Horalabiosa]]'', ''[[Hypselobarbus]]'', ''[[Indoreonectes]]'', ''[[Lepidopygopsis]]'', ''[[Longischistura]]'', ''[[Mesonoemacheilus]]'', ''[[Parapsilorhynchus]]'', ''[[Rohtee]]'' and ''[[Travancoria]]'').<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal>{{cite book|author1=Molur, M. |author2=Smith, K.G. |author3=Daniel, B.A. |author4=Darwall, W.R.T.   |last-author-amp=yes |year=2011|url=https://portals.iucn.org/library/sites/library/files/documents/RL-540-001.pdf|title=The status and distribution of freshwater biodiversity in the Western Ghats, India|publisher=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species \u2013 Regional Assessment|isbn=978-2-8317-1381-6}}</ref>\n\nThere is a higher fish [[Species richness|richness]] in the southern part of the Western Ghats than in the northern,<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> and the highest is in the [[Chalakudy River]], which alone holds 98 species.<ref name=RaghavanFish>{{cite journal | last1 = Raghavan | last2 = Prasad | last3 = Ali | last4 = Pereira | year = 2008 | title = Fish fauna of Chalakudy River, part of Western Ghats biodiversity hotspot, Kerala, India: patterns of distribution, threats and conservation needs | url = | journal = Biodiversity and Conservation | volume = 17 | issue = 13| pages = 3119\u20133131 | doi=10.1007/s10531-007-9293-0}}</ref> Other rivers with high species numbers include the [[Periyar (river)|Periyar]], [[Bharatapuzha]], [[Pamba River|Pamba]] and [[Chaliyar]], as well as upstream tributaries of the [[Kaveri]], [[Pambar River (Kerala)|Pambar]], [[Bhavani River|Bhavani]] and [[Krishna River|Krishna]] rivers.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> The most species rich families are the [[Cyprinidae|Cyprinids]] (72 species), [[hillstream loach]]es (34 species; including [[Nemacheilidae|stone loaches]], now regarded a separate family), [[Bagridae|Bagrid catfishes]] (19 species) and [[Sisoridae|Sisorid catfishes]] (12 species).<ref name=\"Neelesh Fish\"/><ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/><ref name=RaghavanFish/> The region is home to several brilliantly coloured ornamental fishes like the [[Denison barb|Denison (or red line torpedo) barb]],<ref>Raghavan, R., Philip, S., Ali, A. & Dahanukar, N. (2013): [https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230040/http://www.threatenedtaxa.org/ZooPrintJournal/2013/November/o367326xi134932-4938.pdf ''Sahyadria'', a new genus of barbs (Teleostei: Cyprinidae) from Western Ghats of India.] ''Journal of Threatened Taxa'', 5 (15): 4932-4938.</ref> [[melon barb]], several species of ''[[Dawkinsia]]'' barbs, [[zebra loach]], ''Horabagrus'' catfish, [[dwarf pufferfish]] and [[Carinotetraodon imitator|dwarf Malabar pufferfish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zoologica.lifescience.ntu.edu.tw/Z-10-1/Z-10-1-2.PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040716010207/http://zoologica.lifescience.ntu.edu.tw/Z-10-1/Z-10-1-2.PDF |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 July 2004 |title=Zoologica |access-date=18 December 2006 }}</ref> The rivers are also home to ''[[Osteobrama bakeri]]'', and larger species such as the [[Malabar snakehead]] and [[Tor malabaricus|Malabar mahseer]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Benziger | last2 = Philip | last3 = Raghavan | last4 = Ali | last5 = Sukumaran | last6 = Tharian | last7 = Dahanukar | last8 = Baby | last9 = Peter | last10 = Devi | last11 = Radhakrishnan | last12 = Haniffa | last13 = Britz | last14 = Antunes | year = 2011 | title = Unraveling a 146 Years Old Taxonomic Puzzle: Validation of Malabar Snakehead, Species-Status and Its Relevance for Channid Systematics and Evolution. | journal = PLOS One | volume = 6 | issue = 6| page = e21272 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0021272 | pmid=21731689 | pmc=3123301}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Silas | display-authors = etal   | year = 2005 | title = Indian Journal of Fisheries | volume = 52 | issue = 2| pages = 125\u2013140 }}</ref> A few are adapted to an [[Cavefish|underground life]], including some ''[[Monopterus]]'' swampeels,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gobi | first1 = K.C. | year = 2002 | title = A new synbranchid fish, Monopterus digressus from Kersla, Peninsular India | journal = Rec. Zool. Surv. India | volume = 100 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 137\u2013143 }}</ref> and the catfish ''[[Horaglanis]]'' and ''[[Kryptoglanis]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vincent | first1 = Moncey | last2 = Thomas | first2 = John | date = April 2011 | title = Kryptoglanis shajii, an enigmatic subterranean-spring catfish (Siluriformes, Incertae sedis) from Kerala, India | journal = Ichthyological Research | volume = 58 | issue = 2 | pages = 161\u2013165 | doi = 10.1007/s10228-011-0206-6 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[IUCN]], 97 freshwater fish species from the Western Ghats were considered [[Threatened species|threatened]] in 2011, including 12 critically endangered, 54 endangered and 31 vulnerable.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> All but one (''[[Tor khudree]]'') of these are endemic to the Western Ghats. An additional 26 species from the region are considered [[data deficient]] (their status is unclear at present). The primary threats are from [[habitat loss]], but also from [[overexploitation]] and [[introduced species]].<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/>\n\n===Birds===\nThere are at least 508 bird species. Most of Karnataka's five hundred species of birds are from the Western Ghats region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://karnatakabirds.net |title=Karnataka birds |publisher=karnatakabirds.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060429032225/http://www.karnatakabirds.net/ |archivedate=29 April 2006  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.karnatakaforest.gov.in/English/forest_glance/biodiversity.htm |title=Karnataka forest department (forests at a glance \u2013 Bio-diversity|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927093422/http://www.karnatakaforest.gov.in/English/forest_glance/biodiversity.htm|archive-date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> There are at least 16 species of birds endemic to the Western Ghats including the endangered [[rufous-breasted laughingthrush]], the vulnerable [[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]], [[white-bellied shortwing]] and [[broad-tailed grassbird]], the [[near threatened]] [[grey-breasted laughingthrush]], [[black-and-rufous flycatcher]], [[Nilgiri flycatcher]], and [[Nilgiri pipit]], and the [[least concern]] [[Blue-winged parakeet|Malabar (blue-winged) parakeet]], [[Malabar grey hornbill]], [[white-bellied treepie]], [[grey-headed bulbul]], [[rufous babbler]], [[Wayanad laughingthrush]], [[white-bellied blue-flycatcher]] and the [[crimson-backed sunbird]].<ref name=\"bli\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/ebas/index.html?action=EbaHTMDetails.asp&sid=125&m=0|title=Restricted-range species|year=1998|work=BirdLife EBA Factsheet 12 : Western Ghats|publisher=[[BirdLife International]]|access-date=3 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Columba elphinstonii.jpg|[[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]]\nFile:Great-Hornbill.jpg|[[Great hornbill]]\nFile:Crimson-fronted Barbet (Megalaima rubricapilla) - Male - Sakleshpur - India -2009.jpg|[[Malabar barbet]]\nFile:2005-malabar-parkeet-p.jpg|[[Blue-winged parakeet|Malabar (blue-winged) parakeet]]\nFile:NilgiriPipit.jpg|[[Nilgiri pipit]]\nFile:White bellied treepie Thattekad.jpg|[[White-bellied treepie]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Insects===\nThere are roughly 6,000 insect species.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Mathew George|author2=Binoy C.F.|lastauthoramp=yes|title=An Overview of Insect Diversity of Western Ghats with Special Reference to Kerala State|access-date=24 July 2007|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter3.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090316112850/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter3.htm|archivedate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Of 334 [[List of Western Ghats butterflies|Western Ghats butterfly]] species, 316 species have been reported from the [[Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve]].<ref>{{Citation|author1=George Mathew|author2=M. Mahesh Kumar|lastauthoramp=yes|title=State of the Art Knowledge on the Butterflies of Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter6.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090108105816/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter6.htm|archivedate=8 January 2009}}</ref> The Western Ghats are home to 174 species of [[odonates]] (107 [[dragonflies]] and 67 [[damselflies]]), including 69 endemics.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> Most of the endemic odonate are closely associated with rivers and streams, while the non-endemics typically are [[Generalist and specialist species|generalists]].<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/>\nThere are several species of [[leech]]es found all along the Western Ghats.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/069/01-04/0325-0328.pdf|title=Collection of leeches from Maharashtra|last=Chandra|first=Mahesh|year=1976|website=Zoological Survey of India|series=69 : 325\u2013328|publisher=Rec. Zool. Surv. India|access-date=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Malabar tree nymph 01.jpg|The [[Malabar tree nymph]] is endemic to the Western Ghats.\nFile:Tamil_Lacewing2_before.jpg|[[Cethosia nietneri|Tamil Lacewings]] are found only in South Asia.\nFile:Ischnura_heterosticta02.jpg|The Western Ghats have 67 species of [[damselflies]].\nFile:SnailWynaad.jpg|The endemic land snail ''[[Indrella ampulla]]''\nFile:Phallus Indusiatus2.jpg|''[[Phallus indusiatus]]'' found in the Western Ghats\n</gallery>\n\n===Molluscs===\nSeasonal rainfall patterns of the Western Ghats necessitate a period of [[diapause|dormancy]] for its [[land snail]]s, resulting in their high abundance and diversity including at least 258 species of [[gastropods]] from 57 genera and 24 families.<ref>{{Citation|author=Madhyastha N. A.|author2=Rajendra|author3=Mavinkurve G.|author4=Shanbhag Sandhya P.|last-author-amp=yes|title=Land Snails of Western Ghats|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter9.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090717093156/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter9.htm|archivedate=17 July 2009}}</ref> A total of 77 species of [[freshwater mollusc]]s (52 gastropods and 25 [[bivalves]]) have been recorded from the Western Ghats, but the actual number is likely higher.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> This include 28 endemics. Among the threatened freshwater molluscs are the mussels ''[[Pseudomulleria dalyi]]'', which is a [[Gondwana]]n relict, and the snail ''[[Cremnoconchus]]'', which is restricted to the spray zone of waterfalls.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> According to the IUCN, 4 species of freshwater molluscs are considered endangered and 3 are vulnerable. An additional 19 species are considered data deficient.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/>\n\n==Flora==\nOf the 7,402 species of flowering plants occurring in the Western Ghats, 5,588 species are native or indigenous and 376 are exotics naturalised; 1,438 species are cultivated or planted as ornamentals. Among the indigenous species, 2,253 species are endemic to India and of them, 1,273 species are exclusively confined to the Western Ghats. Apart from 593 confirmed subspecies and varieties; 66 species, 5 subspecies and 14 varieties of doubtful occurrence are also reported, amounting to 8,080 taxa of flowering plants.<ref>Nayar, T.S., Rasiya Beegam A., and M. Sibi. (2014). Flowering Plants of the Western Ghats, India (2 Volumes), Jawaharlal Nehru Tropical Botanic Garden and Research Institute, Palode, Thiruvananthapuram, Kerala, India. p.1700</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghat Roads]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Mahajan, Harshal. ''A rendezvous with Sahyadri''\n* Ingalhalikar, Shrikant. ''Flowers of Sahyadri''. Corolla Publication; Pune\n* Wikramanayake, Eric; Eric Dinerstein; Colby J. Loucks; et al. (2002). ''Terrestrial Ecoregions of the Indo-Pacific: a Conservation Assessment.'' Island Press; Washington, DC.\n* Kapadia, Harish. ''Trek the Sahyadris''\n* [https://archive.is/20070228195706/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter2.htm Daniels, R.J. Ranjit, Wildlife institute of India, \"Biodiversity in the Western Ghats\"]\n* Ajith Kumar, [[S\u00e1lim Ali Centre for Ornithology and Natural History]], Coimbatore, India, Ravi Chellam, B.C.Choudhury, Divya Mudappa, Karthikeyan Vasudevan, N.M.Ishwar, Wildlife Institute of India, Dehra Dun, India, Barry Noon, Department of Fish and Wildlife Biology, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, U.S. (2002) \"''Impact of Rainforest Fragmentation on Small Mammals and Herpetofauna in the Western Ghats, South India''\", [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070701040125/http://www.wii.gov.in/faculty/publication/frag.wii.report.pdf Final Report, pp. 146, illus. Full text] retrieved 14 March 2007\n* Verma Desh Deepak (2002) \"''Thematic Report on Mountain Ecosystems''\", Ministry of Environment and Forests,13pp, retrieved 27 March 2007 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060618233452/http://biodiv.org/doc/world/in/in-nr-me-en.doc Thematic Report on Mountain Ecosystems] Full text, detailed data, not cited.\n* Abstracts, Edited by Lalitha Vijayan, Saconr. Vasudeva, University of Dharwad, Priyadarsanan, ATREE, Renee Borges, CES, ISSC, Jagdish Krishnaswamy, Atree & WCSP. Pramod, Sacon, Jagannatha Rao, R., FRLHTR. J. Ranjit Daniels, Care Earth, Compiled by S. Somasundaram, Sacon (1\u20132 December 2005) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130511231752/http://www.westernghatsforum.org/abstract_12_05.pdf ''Integrating Science and Management of Biodiversity in the Western Ghats''], 2nd National Conference of the Western Ghats Forum, Venue: State Forest Service College Coimbatore, Organized by [[S\u00e1lim Ali Centre for Ornithology and Natural History]], Anaikatty, Coimbatore \u2013 641108, India. Sponsored by Ministry of Environment and Forests, Government of India. Supported by The Arghyam Foundation, The Ford Foundation & Sir Dorabiji Trust Through Ashoka Trust for Research in Ecology and the Environment (ATREE)\n* [http://www.ces.iisc.ernet.in/biodiversity/sahyadri_enews/newsletter/issue30/M%20D%20S%20Chandran.pdf Shifting Cultivation, Sacred Groves and Conflicts in Colonial Forest Policy in the Western Ghats.] M.D. Subash Chandran; Chapter 22\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Western Ghats}}\n{{Sister project links}}\n{{wikivoyage}}\n* [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342 Western Ghats], UNESCO World Heritage site\n* [http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/where_we_work/western_ghats/ Western Ghats], WWF\n{{Portal bar|India|Ecology}}\n{{GeoSouthAsia}}\n{{Western Ghats}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in India}}\n{{Mountain passes of India}}\n\n[[Category:Western Ghats| ]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of India]]\n[[Category:Physiographic provinces]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in India]]\n[[Category:Geography of Coimbatore]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Goa]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Mountains in Buddhism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mountain range along the western coast of India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Western Ghats\n| other_name =\n| photo=Western_Ghats_Gobi.jpg\n| photo_caption= The Western Ghats as seen from [[Gobichettipalayam]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| state= [[Gujarat]]\n| state1= [[Maharashtra]]\n| state2= [[Goa]]\n| state3= [[Karnataka]]\n| state4= [[Kerala]]\n| state5= [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| region= [[Western India]]\n| region1= [[Southern India]]\n| city1 = [[Surat]]\n| city2 = [[Mumbai]]\n| city3 = [[Pune]]\n| city4 = [[Kolhapur]]\n| city5 = [[Sirsi, Karnataka]]\n| city6 = [[Shivamogga]]\n| city7 = [[Chikkamagalur]]\n| city8 = [[Mangalore]]\n| city9 = [[Madikeri]]\n| city10 = [[Erode]]\n| city11 = [[Coimbatore]]\n| city12 = [[Kochi]]\n| city13 = [[Tenkasi]]\n| city14 = [[Tirunelveli]]\n| city15 = [[Thiruvananthapuram]]\n| geology = [[Basalt]]\n| geology1= [[Laterite]]\n| geology2 = [[Limestone]]\n| period = [[Cenozoic]]\n| biome = [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests]]\n<!-- *** Geography *** -->\n| area_km2= 160000\n| length_km= 1600\n| length_orientation= N\u2013S\n| width_km= 100\n| width_orientation= E\u2013W\n| highest= [[Anamudi]], [[Kerala]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord|10|10|N|77|04|E|type:mountain|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| highest_location= [[Eravikulam National Park]]\n| elevation_m       = 2695\n| image_map=Satellite Picture of the Western Ghats & Indian West Coast.png\n| map_caption= The Western Ghats lie roughly parallel to the west coast of India.\n| embedded ={{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n| child = yes\n| ID = 1342\n| Year = 2012\n| Criteria = Natural: ix, x\n| Area = 795,315 ha\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Western Ghats''', also known as '''Sahyadri''' (Benevolent Mountains), are a mountain range that covers an area of {{convert|140000|km2}} in a stretch of {{convert|1600|km}} parallel to the western coast of the [[India]]n peninsula, traversing the states of [[Kerala]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Karnataka]], [[Goa]], [[Maharashtra]] and [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Western Ghats|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342}}</ref> It is a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] and is one of the eight \"hottest hot-spots\" of [[biological diversity]] in the world.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Biodiversity hotspots for conservation priorities|journal=Nature|volume=403|issue=6772|pages=853\u2013858|doi=10.1038/35002501|pmid=10706275|year=2000|last1=Myers|first1=Norman|last2=Mittermeier|first2=Russell A.|last3=Mittermeier|first3=Cristina G.|last4=Da Fonseca|first4=Gustavo A. B.|last5=Kent|first5=Jennifer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-02/flora-fauna/32507340_1_world-heritage-list-western-ghats-border-town|title=UN designates Western Ghats as world heritage site|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date=2 July 2012|access-date=2 July 2012}}</ref> It is sometimes called the Great [[Escarpment]] of India.<ref>{{cite book|last=Migon|first=Piotr|title=Geomorphological Landscapes of the World|date=12 May 2010|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-90-481-3054-2|page=257}}</ref> It contains a large proportion of the country's [[flora]] and [[fauna]], many of which are only found in India and nowhere else in the world.<ref>{{citation|title=A biodiversity hotspot|url=http://wwf.panda.org/knowledge_hub/where_we_work/western_ghats/}}</ref> According to [[UNESCO]], the Western Ghats are older than the [[Himalayas]]. They influence Indian monsoon weather patterns by intercepting the rain-laden monsoon winds that sweep in from the south-west during late summer.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The range runs north to south along the western edge of the [[Deccan Plateau]], and separates the plateau from a narrow coastal plain, called [[Konkan]], along the [[Arabian Sea]]. A total of thirty-nine areas in the Western Ghats, including national parks, wildlife sanctuaries and reserve forests, were designated as world heritage sites in 2012 \u2013 twenty in [[Kerala]], ten in [[Karnataka]], five in [[Tamil Nadu]] and four in [[Maharashtra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342/multiple=1&unique_number=1921|title=Western Ghats|work=[[UNESCO]]|access-date=3 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Clara|last=Lewis|date=3 July 2012|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-03/mumbai/32523277_1_radhanagari-wildlife-world-heritage-centre-western-ghats|title=39 sites in Western Ghats get world heritage status |newspaper=[[Times of India]]|access-date=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe range starts near the [[Songadh]] town of [[Gujarat]], south of the [[Tapti river]], and runs approximately {{convert|1600|km|abbr=on}} through the states of [[Maharashtra]], [[Goa]], [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Tamil Nadu]] ending at [[Marunthuvazh Malai]], at [[Swamithope]], near the southern tip of India. These hills cover {{convert|160000|km2|abbr=on}} and form the catchment area for complex riverine [[Drainage system (geomorphology)|drainage systems]] that drain almost 40% of India. The Western Ghats block [[southwest monsoon]] winds from reaching the Deccan Plateau.{{cn|date=March 2020}} The average elevation is around {{convert|1200|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"APMN\">{{cite web|url=http://apmn.icimod.org/mountains/ch2_peninsula.php|title= The Peninsula|access-date=19 March 2007|work=Asia-Pacific Mountain Network |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070812064356/http://apmn.icimod.org/mountains/ch2_peninsula.php|archive-date=12 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe area is one of the world's ten \"hottest [[biodiversity hotspot]]s\" and has over 7,402 species of flowering plants, 1,814 species of non-flowering plants, 139 mammal species, 508 bird species, 179 amphibian species, 6,000 insects species and 290 freshwater fish species; it is likely that many undiscovered species live in the Western Ghats. At least 325 globally [[threatened species]] occur in the Western Ghats.<ref name=\"Flowering plants\">{{cite book |last1=Nayar |first1=T.S. |last2=Rasiya Beegam |first2=A |last3=Sibi |first3=M. |title=Flowering Plants of the Western Ghats, India (2 Volumes) |date=2014 |publisher=Jawaharlal Nehru Tropical Botanic Garden and Research Institute. p.1700|location=Thiruvananthapuram, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Myers |first1=N. |last2=Mittermeier |first2=R.A. |last3=Mittermeier |first3=C.G. |last4=Fonseca |first4=G.A.B.Da |last5=Kent |first5=J. |year=2000 |title=Biodiversity Hotspots for Conservation Priorities |journal=Nature |volume=403 |issue=6772 |pages=853\u2013858 |doi=10.1038/35002501 |pmid=10706275}}</ref><ref name=\"Neelesh Fish\">{{cite journal |last1=Dahanukar |first1=N. |last2=Raut |first2=R. |last3=Bhat |first3=A. |year=2004 |title=Distribution, endemism and threat status of freshwater fishes in the Western Ghats of India |journal=Journal of Biogeography |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=123\u2013136 |doi=10.1046/j.0305-0270.2003.01016.x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/5c915245a382eabc0650d1e37492c57e6c59e70e }}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word [[ghat]] is explained by numerous [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] etymons such as [[Tamil language|Tamil]] gattu (hill and hill forest), [[Kannada language|Kannada]] ''gaati'' and ''ghatta'' (mountain range), [[Tulu language|Tulu]] ''gatta'' (hill or hillside),  and ''ghattam'' in [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] (mountainous way, riverside and hairpin bends).<ref>{{cite book|last=Jaini|first=Padmanabh S.|title=Jainism and Early Buddhism|year=2003|publisher=Jain Publishing Company|pages=523\u2013538|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5_EdL2FtIqQC&dq=etymology+dravidian|isbn=9780895819567}}</ref>\n\n''Ghat'', a term used in the [[Indian subcontinent]], depending on the context could either refer to a [[Geography of India#Coastal plains and ghats|range of stepped-hill]] such as the [[Eastern Ghats]] and Western Ghats; or the series of steps leading down to a body of water or [[wharf]], such bathing or cremation place along the banks of a river or pond, [[Ghats in Varanasi]], [[Dhoby Ghaut]] or [[Aapravasi Ghat]].<ref name=dict1>Sunithi L. Narayan, Revathy Nagaswami, 1992, [https://books.google.com/books?id=miZuAAAAMAAJ&q=ghat+means&dq=ghat+means&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_nZnwjpPgAhUHWysKHQcdAjk4ChDoAQgpMAA Discover sublime India: handbook for tourists], Page 5.</ref><ref name=dict2>[https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/ghat Ghat definition], Cambridge dictionary.</ref> Roads passing through ghats are called [[Ghat Roads]].\n\n==Geology==\nThe Western Ghats are the mountainous [[Fault (geology)|faulted]] and [[Erosion|eroded]] edge of the [[Deccan Plateau]]. Geologic evidence indicates that they were formed during the break-up of the supercontinent of [[Gondwana]] some 150 million years ago. [[geophysics|Geophysical]] evidence indicates that the west coast of India came into being somewhere around 100 to 80 [[mya (unit)|mya]] after it broke away from [[Madagascar]]. After the break-up, the western coast of India would have appeared as an abrupt cliff some {{convert|1000|m|abbr=on}} in [[elevation]].<ref name=\"Barron, E.J.\">{{cite journal |last1=Barron |first1=E.J. |last2=Harrison |first2= C.G.A. |last3=Sloan |first3=J.L. II |last4=Hay |first4=W.W. |year=1981 |title= Paleogeography, 180 million years ago to the present |journal=Eclogae Geologicae Helvetiae |volume=74 |issue=2 |pages=443\u2013470}}</ref> [[Basalt]] is the predominant rock found in the hills reaching a thickness of {{convert|3|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}. Other rock types found are [[charnockite]]s, [[granite]] gneiss, [[khondalite]]s, [[leptynite]]s, metamorphic [[gneiss]]es with detached occurrences of crystalline [[limestone]], iron ore, [[dolerite]]s and [[anorthosite]]s. Residual [[laterite]] and [[bauxite]] ores are also found in the southern hills.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Tamil Nadu topo deutsch mit Gebirgen.png|thumb|Topography: Western Ghats (southern part)]]\nThe Western Ghats extend from the [[Satpura Range]] in the north, stretching from [[Gujarat]] to [[Tamil Nadu]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} It traverses south through the states of [[Maharashtra]], [[Goa]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Kerala]]. Major gaps in the range are the [[Goa Gap]], between the Maharashtra and Karnataka sections, and the [[Palghat Gap]] on the Tamil Nadu and Kerala border between the Nilgiri Hills and the [[Anaimalai Hills]]. The mountains intercept the rain-bearing westerly [[monsoon]] winds, and are consequently an area of high rainfall, particularly on their western side. The dense forests also contribute to the precipitation of the area by acting as a substrate for condensation of moist rising [[orographic]] winds from the sea, and releasing much of the moisture back into the air via [[transpiration]], allowing it to later condense and fall again as rain.\n\nThe northern portion of the narrow coastal plain between the Western Ghats and the [[Arabian Sea]] is known as the [[Konkan Coast|Konkan]], the central portion is called [[Kanara]] and the southern portion is called [[Malabar Coast|Malabar]]. The foothill region east of the Ghats in [[Maharashtra]] is known as [[Desh, Maharashtra|Desh]], while the eastern foothills of the central Karnataka state is known as [[Malenadu]].<ref name=\"all-about-india.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.all-about-india.com/Geography-of-India.html|title=The Geography of India|publisher=all-about-india.com|access-date=19 November 2010}}</ref> The range is known as ''Sahyadri'' in [[Maharashtra]] and [[Karnataka]]. The Western Ghats meet the [[Eastern Ghats]] at the [[Nilgiri mountains]] in northwestern [[Tamil Nadu]]. The Nilgiris connect the [[Biligiriranga Hills]] in southeastern Karnataka with the [[Shevaroys]] and [[Tirumala]] hills. South of the [[Palghat Gap]] are the [[Anamala Hills]], located in western Tamil Nadu and Kerala with smaller ranges further south, including the [[Cardamom Hills]], then [[Aryankavu]] pass, and [[Aralvaimozhi]] pass near Kanyakumari. The range is known as ''Sahyan'' or ''Sahian'' in [[Kerala]]. In the southern part of the range is [[Anamudi]] ({{convert|2695|m|ft|0}}), the highest peak in the Western Ghats.\n\n===Peaks===\n{{Main|List of peaks in the Western Ghats}}\nThe Western Ghats have many peaks that rise above 2,000 meters, with [[Anamudi]] ({{convert|2695|m|ft|abbr=on}}) being the highest peak.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Water bodies===\n[[File:Varandha ghad.jpg|thumb|View from Varandha Pass Mahad showing the numerous waterfalls]]\nThe Western Ghats form one of the four [[Drainage basin|watersheds]] of India, feeding the perennial rivers of India. The major river systems originating in the Western Ghats are the [[Godavari river|Godavari]], [[Kaveri river|Kaveri]], [[Krishna river|Krishna]], [[Thamiraparani]] and [[Tungabhadra]] rivers. The majority of streams draining the Western Ghats join these rivers, and carry a large volume of water during the monsoon months. These rivers flow to the east due to the gradient of the land and drain out into the [[Bay of Bengal]]. Major tributaries include the [[Kali River (Karnataka)|Kali]], [[Bhadra river|Bhadra]], [[Bhavani river|Bhavani]], [[Bhima River|Bhima]], [[Malaprabha River|Malaprabha]], [[Ghataprabha River|Ghataprabha]], [[Hemavathi river|Hemavathi]] and [[Kabini River|Kabini]] rivers. The [[Periyar River|Periyar]], [[Bharathappuzha]], [[Pamba River|Pamba]], [[Netravati River|Netravati]], [[Sharavathi]], [[Mandovi]] and [[Zuari River|Zuari]] rivers flow westwards towards the Western Ghats, draining into the [[Arabian Sea]], and are fast-moving, owing to the steeper gradient.\n\n[[File:Jog Falls, India - August 2006.jpg|thumb|left|[[Jog Falls]] in Karnataka, one of the most spectacular waterfalls in India]]\nThe rivers have been dammed for [[hydroelectric]] and [[irrigation]] purposes with major reservoirs spread across the states. The reservoirs are important for their commercial and sport fisheries of [[rainbow trout]], [[mahseer]] and [[common carp]].<ref name=SehgalFish>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/003/x2614e/x2614e06.htm|last=Sehgal|first=K. L.|title= Coldwater fish and fisheries in the Western Ghats, India|publisher=[[FAO]]|access-date=22 September 2008}}</ref> There are about 50 major dams along the length of the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/resources/statistics/stat233.htm|title=Indian Dams by River and State|publisher=Rain water harvesting|access-date=19 March 2007}}</ref> Most notable of these projects are the [[Koyna Hydroelectric Project|Koyna]] in Maharashtra, [[Linganmakki Dam|Linganmakki]] and [[Shivanasamudra]] in Karnataka, [[Mettur Dam|Mettur]] and [[Pykara]] in Tamil Nadu, [[Parambikulam Dam|Parambikulam]], [[Malampuzha Dam|Malampuzha]] and [[Idukki dam|Idukki]] in Kerala.<ref name=\"all-about-india.com\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Rajesh|last=Menon|url=http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=151253|title=Tremors may rock Koyna for another two-decade|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|date=3 October 2005|access-date=19 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117083928/http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=151253|archive-date=17 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first1=R.L.|last1=Samani|first2=A.P.|last2=Ayhad|title=Silting Problems in Hydropower Plants|editor=S. P. Kaushish|editor2=B. S. K. Naidu|publisher=Central Board of Irrigation and Power|location=Bangkok|year=2002|chapter=Siltation of Reservoirs-Koyna Hydroelectric Project-A Case Study|isbn=978-90-5809-238-0}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Banasura sagar.jpg|thumb|right|[[Banasura Sagar Dam]]]]\nDuring the monsoon season, numerous streams fed by incessant rain drain off the mountain sides leading to numerous waterfalls. Major waterfalls include [[Dudhsagar Falls|Dudhsagar]], [[Unchalli Falls|Unchalli]],\n[[Sathodi Falls|Sathodi]], [[Magod Falls|Magod]], [[Hogenakkal Falls|Hogenakkal]], [[Jog Falls|Jog]], [[Kunchikal Falls|Kunchikal]], [[Shivanasamudra Falls|Shivanasamudra]], [[Meenmutty Falls, Wayanad|Meenmutty Falls]], [[Athirappilly Falls]]. [[Talakaveri]] is the source of the river Kaveri and the Kuduremukha range is the source of the Tungabhadra. The Western Ghats have several man-made lakes and reservoirs with major lakes at [[Ooty Lake|Ooty]] ({{convert|34|ha}}) in Nilgiris, [[Kodaikanal Lake|Kodaikanal]] ({{convert|26|ha}}) and [[Berijam Lake|Berijam]] in [[Palani Hills]], [[Pookode lake]], Karlad Lake in [[Wayanad]], [[Vagamon]] lake, [[Devikulam]] ({{convert|6|ha}}) and Letchmi ({{convert|2|ha}}) in [[Idukki]], Kerala.\n[[File:Chembra Peak seen from Pookode Lake.JPG|thumb|Chembra Peak seen from Pookode Lake]]\n\n==Climate==\n[[File:Western-Ghats-rainfall.svg|thumb|upright|Annual rainfall along the Western Ghat region]]\nThe area including [[Agumbe]], [[Hulikal]] and [[Amagaon]] in [[Karnataka]], Mahabaleshwar and Tamhini in [[Maharashtra]] are often referred to as the \"[[Cherrapunji]] of southwest India\" or the \"rain capital of southwest India\". [[Kollur, Udupi district|Kollur in Udupi district]], Kokkali and [[Nilkund]] in [[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Samse]] in [[Mudigere]] of [[Karnataka]], and [[Neriamangalam]] in the [[Ernakulam district]] of [[Kerala]] are the wettest places in the Western Ghats. Heavy precipitation does occur in the surrounding regions due to the long continuity of the mountains without passes and gaps. Changes in the direction and pace of the wind do affect the average rainfall and the wettest places might vary. However, [[Maharashtra]] and the northern part of Western Ghats in [[Karnataka]] on average receive heavier rainfall than [[Kerala]] and the southern part of Western Ghats in Karnataka.\n\nThe climate in the Western Ghats varies with altitudinal gradation and distance from the equator. The climate is humid and tropical in the lower reaches tempered by the proximity to the sea. Elevations of {{convert|1500|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} and above in the north and {{convert|2000|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} and above in the south have a more temperate climate. The average annual temperature is around {{convert|15|\u00b0C}}. In some parts frost is common, and temperatures reach the freezing point during the winter months. Mean temperatures range from {{convert|20|\u00b0C}} in the south to {{convert|24|\u00b0C}} in the north. It has also been observed that the coldest periods in the South Western Ghats coincide with the wettest.<ref name=\"WII\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter2.htm|first=R.J.|last=Ranjit Daniels|title=Biodiversity of the Western Ghats \u2013 An Overview|access-date=19 March 2007|work=Wildlife Institute of India|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070228195706/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter2.htm|archivedate=28 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[monsoon|monsoon season]] between June and September, the unbroken Western Ghats chain acts as a barrier to the moisture-laden clouds. The heavy, eastward-moving rain-bearing clouds are forced to rise and in the process deposit most of their rain on the windward side. Rainfall in this region averages {{convert|300|cm}} to {{convert|400|cm}} with localised extremes reaching {{convert|900|cm}}. The eastern regions of the Western Ghats, which lie in the [[rain shadow]], receive far less rainfall (about {{convert|100|cm}}), resulting in an average rainfall of {{convert|250|cm}} across all regions. The total amount of rain does not depend on the spread of the area; areas in northern Maharashtra receive heavy rainfall followed by long dry spells, while regions closer to the equator receive less annual rainfall and have rain spells lasting several months in a year.<ref name=\"WII\"/>\n\n===Rainfall===\nThe Karnataka region on average receives heavier rainfall than the Kerala, Maharashtra and Goa. Meanwhile, the Ghats in Karnataka have fewer passes and gaps and therefore the western slopes of Karnataka receive heavy rainfall, over 400&nbsp;cm more than other regional parts of the Western Ghats.\n\nSome of the wettest places in the Western Ghats are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Region\n!Mean annual rainfall<ref>https://en.climate-data.org</ref>\n|-\n|[[Agumbe]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Thirthahalli|[[Thirthahalli]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|7624|{{convert|7624|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Amboli, Sindhudurg|Amboli]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Sindhudurg|[[Sindhudurg district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|3859|{{convert|3859|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Hulikal]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Hosanagara|[[Hosanagara]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|5316|{{convert|5316|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Amagaon]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Khanapur|[[Khanapur]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4089|{{convert|4089|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Kakkali|Kakkalli]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada, Sirsi|[[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4921|{{convert|4921|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Nilkund]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada, Sirsi|[[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4369|{{convert|4369|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Mahabaleshwar]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Satara|[[Satara district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|5761|{{convert|5761|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Devimane Ghat|Devimane]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada, Sirsi|[[Sirsi, Karnataka|Sirsi]], [[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|3981|{{convert|3981|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Surli]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Hosanagara|[[Hosanagara]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4335|{{convert|4335|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Lonavla]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Pune|[[Pune district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|4073|{{convert|4073|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Charmadi]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Mudigere|[[Mudigere]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4131|{{convert|4131|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Samse]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Mudigere|[[Mudigere]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|3914|{{convert|3914|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Kollur, Udupi district|Kollur]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Udupi|[[Udupi district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4992|{{convert|4992|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Makkiyad]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Wayanad|[[Wayanad district]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|3714|{{convert|3714|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Kudremukh]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Chikmagalur|[[Chikmagalur district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|4158|{{convert|4158|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Rajamalai]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Idukki|[[Idukki]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|4785|{{convert|4785|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Nyamakad]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Idukki|[[Idukki]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|3007|{{convert|3007|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Sholayar]]\n|{{sort|Tamil Nadu, Coimbatore|[[Coimbatore]], [[Tamil Nadu]]}}\n|{{sort|3024|{{convert|3024|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Vythiri]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Wayanad|[[Wayanad district]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|4000|{{convert|4000|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Pookode]]\n|{{sort|Kerala, Wayanad|[[Wayanad district]], [[Kerala]]}}\n|{{sort|3957|{{convert|3957|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Dhamanohol]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Mulshi taluka|[[Mulshi taluka]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|6255|{{convert|6255|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Mulshi]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Pune|[[Pune district]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|5100|{{convert|5100|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Tamhini Ghat]]\n|{{sort|Maharashtra, Mulshi taluka|[[Mulshi taluka]], [[Maharashtra]]}}\n|{{sort|5255|{{convert|5255|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Chinnakallar Falls|Chinnakallar]]\n|{{sort|Tamil Nadu, Coimbatore|[[Coimbatore]], [[Tamil Nadu]]}}\n|{{sort|2947|{{convert|2947|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|-\n|[[Castle Rock, Karnataka|Castle Rock]]\n|{{sort|Karnataka, Uttara Kannada|[[Uttara Kannada|Uttara Kannada district]], [[Karnataka]]}}\n|{{sort|5132|{{convert|5132|mm|in|abbr=on}}}}\n|}\n\n==Ecoregions==\n[[File:Shola.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sholas]], part of the rainforests]]\nThe Western Ghats are home to four [[tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forest]] [[ecoregions]] \u2013 the [[North Western Ghats moist deciduous forests]], [[North Western Ghats montane rain forests]], [[South Western Ghats moist deciduous forests]], and [[South Western Ghats montane rain forests]]. The northern portion of the range is generally drier than the southern portion, and at lower elevations makes up the North Western Ghats moist deciduous forests ecoregion, with mostly deciduous forests made up predominantly of [[teak]]. Above 1,000 meters elevation are the cooler and wetter [[North Western Ghats montane rain forests]], whose evergreen forests are characterised by trees of the family ''[[Lauraceae]]''.\n\nThe evergreen forests in [[Wayanad]] mark the transition zone between the northern and southern ecoregions of the Western Ghats. The southern ecoregions are generally wetter and more species-rich. At lower elevations are the [[South Western Ghats moist deciduous forests]], with ''[[Cullenia]]'' the characteristic tree genus, accompanied by teak, [[dipterocarp]]s, and other trees. The moist forests transition to the drier [[South Deccan Plateau dry deciduous forests]], which lie in its rain shadow to the east. Above 1,000 meters are the [[South Western Ghats montane rain forests]], also cooler and wetter than the surrounding lowland forests, and dominated by evergreen trees, although some [[montane grassland]]s and stunted forests can be found at the highest elevations. The South Western Ghats montane rain forests are the most species-rich ecoregion in peninsular India; eighty percent of the [[flowering plant]] species of the entire Western Ghats range are found in this ecoregion.\n\n==Biodiversity protection==\n[[File:Western ghaats1, maharashtra.jpg|thumb|Dense rainforests cover the Western Ghats.]]\n[[File:Heavenly Sahyadri.jpg|thumb|The Western Ghats are a UNESCO heritage site.]]\nHistorically the Western Ghats were covered in dense forests that provided wild foods and natural habitats for native [[Indigenous peoples|tribal people]]. Its inaccessibility made it difficult for people from the [[Deccan Plateau|plains]] to cultivate the land and build settlements. After the arrival of the [[British empire#Expansion|British]] in the area, large swathes of territory were cleared for agricultural plantations and timber. The forest in the Western Ghats has been severely fragmented due to human activities, especially [[clear-felling]] for tea, coffee, and teak plantations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.manoramaonline.com/travel/beyond-kerala/2019/06/11/camp-worlds-highest-tea-estate-kolukkumalai-munnat-drive.html|title=Camp at world's highest tea estate Kolukkumalai|website=OnManorama|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> from 1860 to 1950.  Species that are rare, [[Endemism|endemic]] and habitat specialists are more adversely affected and tend to be lost faster than other species. Complex and species rich habitats like the tropical rainforest are much more adversely affected than other habitats.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2002/frag.wii.report.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20081219184202/http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2002/frag.wii.report.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 December 2008|title=Impact of rainforest fragmentation on small mammals and herpetofauna in the Western Ghats, South India|first=Ajith|last=Kumar|publisher=Salim Centre for Ornithology and Natural History, Coimbatore}}</ref>\n\nThe area is ecologically sensitive to development and was declared an ecological hotspot in 1988 through the efforts of ecologist [[Norman Myers]]. The area covers five percent of India's land; 27% of all species of higher plants in India (4,000 of 15,000 species) are found here and 1,800 of these are endemic to the region. The range is home to at least 84 amphibian species, 16 bird species, seven mammals, and 1,600 flowering plants which are not found elsewhere in the world. The [[Government of India]] has established many [[protected areas of India|protected areas]] including 2 [[Biosphere reserves of India|biosphere reserves]], 13 [[national parks of India|national parks]] to restrict human access, several [[Wildlife sanctuaries of India|wildlife sanctuaries]] to protect specific endangered species and many [[Reserved forests and protected forests of India|reserve forests]], which are all managed by the forest departments of their respective state to preserve some of the ecoregions still undeveloped. The [[Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve]], comprising {{convert|5500|km2}} of the evergreen forests of [[Nagarahole]] and deciduous forests of [[Bandipur National Park|Bandipur]] in Karnataka, adjoining regions of [[Wayanad]]-[[Mukurthi National Park|Mukurthi]] in Kerala and [[Mudumalai National Park]]-[[Sathyamangalam Wildlife Sanctuary|Sathyamangalam]] in Tamil Nadu, forms the largest contiguous protected area in the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cpreec.org/04_phamplets/08_nilgiri_bio_reser/nilgiri_bio_reser.html|title= The Nilgiri Bio-sphere Reserve|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928151229/http://www.cpreec.org/04_phamplets/08_nilgiri_bio_reser/nilgiri_bio_reser.html |archive-date=28 September 2006}}</ref> [[Silent Valley National Park|Silent Valley]] in Kerala is among the last tracts of virgin tropical evergreen forest in India.<ref name=\"wg\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/article52465.ece|title=No clearance for mining, hydel projects that destroy Western Ghat|last=Ramesh|date=21 November 2009|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|publisher=Kasturi & Sons Ltd.|access-date=29 December 2009|location=Palakkad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/08/04/stories/2009080456210300.htm|title=Gundia project has not got Centre's nod|last=staff|work=The Hindu |publisher=Kasturi & Sons Ltd.|access-date=29 December 2009|location=Chennai, India|date=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, the Western Ghats Ecology Expert Panel (WGEEP) designated the entire Western Ghats as an Ecologically Sensitive Area (ESA) and assigned three levels of Ecological Sensitivity to its different regions.<ref name=\"WGEP\">{{cite journal|url=http://moef.nic.in/downloads/public-information/wg-23052012.pdf|title=Report of the Western Ghats Ecology Expert Panel|author= Madhav Gadgil|publisher= Ministry of Environment and Forests, Government of India|date=2012-08-31|access-date=4 May 2012|website= Westernghatindia.org|volume=Part 1|pages= summary XIX}}</ref> The panel, headed by ecologist [[Madhav Gadgil]], was appointed by the Union [[Ministry of Environment and Forests]] to assess the biodiversity and environmental issues of the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/395071/vested-interests-harm-western-ghats.html|title=Vested interests in Western Ghats|newspaper=[[Deccan Herald]]|access-date=5 May 2016}}</ref> The [[Gadgil Committee]] and its successor, the Kasturirangan Committee, recommended suggestions to protect the Western Ghats. The Gadgil report was criticised as being too environment-friendly and the Kasturirangan report was labelled as being anti-environmental.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/kasturirangan-report-is-antienvironmental/article5533619.ece|title=Report is anti environmental|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/interview/the-kasturirangan-report-is-a-disaster-for-the-western-ghats/20131230.htm|title=Disaster for Western Ghats}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/paradise-lost/article1-1179300.aspx|title=Paradise lost|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|access-date=14 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, India applied to the [[UNESCO]] [[Man and the Biosphere Programme]] (MAB) for the Western Ghats to be listed as a protected [[List of World Heritage Sites in India|World Heritage Site]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|year=2007|title=World Heritage sites, Tentative lists, Western Ghats sub cluster|access-date=30 March 2007|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2103/}}</ref> In 2012, the following places were declared as World Heritage Sites:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342/multiple=1&unique_number=1921|title=UNESCO heritage sites|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|access-date=30 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/flora-fauna/UN-designates-Western-Ghats-as-world-heritage-site/articleshow/14595602.cms |title=UN designates Western Ghats as world heritage site|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|date=2 July 2012|access-date=28 July 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n* [[Kali Tiger Reserve]], [[Dandeli]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Indira Gandhi Wildlife Sanctuary and National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* Mundigekere Bird Sanctuary, [[Sirsi, Karnataka]]\n* [[Kalakkad Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Thattekad Bird Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Shendurney Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Neyyar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Peppara Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Periyar Tiger Reserve]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Srivilliputtur Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Eravikulam National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Grass Hills National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Kerala]]\n* [[Karian Shola National Park]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Sathyamangalam Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Chinnar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Silent Valley National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Mukurthi National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Pushpagiri Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Brahmagiri Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* Mookambika Wildlife Sanctuary\n* [[Talakaveri Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Aralam Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Kudremukh National Park]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Someshwara Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Kaas Plateau]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Bhimashankar Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Koyna Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Chandoli National Park]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Radhanagari Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Maharashtra]]\n* [[Parambikulam Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Pambadum Shola National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Anamudi Shola National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Chimmony Wildlife Sanctuary]]\n* [[Peechi-Vazhani Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Mathikettan Shola National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Kurinjimala Sanctuary]], [[Kerala]]\n* [[Karimpuzha National Park]], [[Kerala]]\n* Idukki Wildlife Sanctuary\n* Ranipuram National Park\n* [[Megamalai Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Palani Hills Wildlife Sanctuary and National Park]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Kanyakumari Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Bandipur National Park]] [[Megamalai Wildlife Sanctuary|,]] [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Nagarhole National Park]], [[Karnataka]]\n* [[Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Fauna==\nThe Western Ghats are home to thousands of animal species including at least 325 globally [[threatened species]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mammals of the Western Ghats: A Simplistic Overview|first1=P.O.|last1=Nameer|first2=Sanjay|last2=Molur|first3=Sally|last3=Walker|date=November 2001|journal=Zoos' Print Journal|volume=16|issue=11|pages=629\u2013639|doi=10.11609/jott.zpj.16.11.629-39|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a782a69ce9472a58528e2cfbb98e13be3483f992}}</ref>\n\n===Mammals===\nThere are at least 139 [[mammal]] species. Of the 16 endemic mammals, 13 are threatened. Among the 32 threatened species are the [[critically endangered]] [[Malabar large-spotted civet]], the [[endangered]] [[lion-tailed macaque]], [[Nilgiri tahr]], [[Bengal tiger]] and [[Indian elephant]]s, the [[vulnerable species|vulnerable]] [[Indian leopard]], [[Nilgiri langur]] and [[gaur]].<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Participants of CBSG CAMP workshop: Status of South Asian Primates (March 2002)|year=2004|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/12559/0|title=''Macaca silenus''|access-date=9 May 2006|ref=harv}} Database entry includes justification for why this species is endangered</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mewa|first1=Singh|last2=Werner|first2=Kaumanns|year=2005|title=Behavioural studies: A necessity for wildlife management|url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/oct102005/1230.pdf|journal=Current Science|volume=89|issue=7|page=1233|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070113063948/http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/oct102005/1230.pdf|archivedate=13 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Malviya|first1=M.|last2=Srivastav|first2=A.|last3=Nigam|first3=P.|last4=Tyagi|first4=P.C.|title=Indian National Studbook of Nilgiri Langur (''Trachypithecus johnii'')|url=http://www.cza.nic.in/Nilgiri%20Langur%20studbook.pdf|year=2011|publisher=[[Wildlife Institute of India]], Dehradun and [[Central Zoo Authority]], New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nThese hill ranges serve as important [[wildlife corridor]]s and form an important part of [[Project Elephant]] and [[Project Tiger]] reserves. The largest population of tigers outside the [[Sundarban]]s is in the Western Ghats, where there are seven populations with an estimated population size of 336 to 487 individuals occupying {{convert|21435|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} of forest in three major landscape units spread across Karnataka, Tamil Nadu and Kerala.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Status of the Tigers, co-predators, and Prey in India|last1=Jhala|first1=Y. V.|last2=Gopal|first2=R.|last3=Qureshi|first3=Q|publisher=National Tiger Conservation Authority, Govt. of India, New Delhi; Wildlife Institute of India, Dehradun|year=2008|series=TR 08/001|url=http://projecttiger.nic.in/whtsnew/status_of_tigers_in_india_2008.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602124630/http://projecttiger.nic.in/whtsnew/status_of_tigers_in_india_2008.pdf|archivedate=2 June 2013}}</ref> The Western Ghats ecoregion has the largest Indian elephant population in the wild with an estimated 11,000 individuals across eight distinct populations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiienvis.nic.in/Database/eri_8226.aspx|title= Elephant Reserves|publisher=ENVIS Centre on Wildlife & Protected Areas|access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://envfor.nic.in/pe/PE%20Note.pdf|title=Census population 2005|year=2007|work=Note on Project Elephant|publisher=Ministry of Environment and Forests|access-date=30 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312060920/http://envfor.nic.in/pe/PE%20Note.pdf|archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref> The endemic [[Nilgiri tahr]], which was on the brink of extinction, has recovered and has an estimated 3,122 individuals in the wild.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/nilgiri-tahr-population-over-3000-wwfindia/article7717561.ece|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|title=Nilgiri tahr population over 3,000: WWF-India|date=3 October 2015|access-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> The [[critically endangered]] endemic [[Malabar large-spotted civet]] is estimated to number fewer than 250 mature individuals, with no sub-population greater than 50 individuals.<ref>{{cite iucn|author=Jennings, A.|author2=Veron, G.|author3=Helgen, K.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/23036/0|title=Viverra civettina|ref=harv}}</ref> About 3500 [[lion-tailed macaque]]s live scattered over several areas in the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Molur S|author2=D Brandon-Jones|author3=W Dittus|author4= A. Eudey|author5=A. Kumar|author6= M. Singh|author7=M.M. Feeroz|author8=M. Chalise|author9=P. Priya|author10=S. Walker|last-author-amp=yes|year=2003|title=Status of South Asian Primates: Conservation Assessment and Management Plan (C.A.M.P.) Workshop Report, 2003|publisher=Zoo Outreach Organization/CBSG-South Asia, Coimbatore}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Bengal_Tiger_Karnataka.jpg|The Western Ghats have the largest [[Bengal tiger|tiger]] population outside [[Sunderbans]].\nFile:Lightmatter lion-tailed macaque.jpg|The endangered [[lion-tailed macaque]] is endemic to the Western Ghats.\nFile:Elephas maximus (Bandipur).jpg|The Western Ghats region has the largest [[Indian elephant]] population in India.\nFile:Nilgiritragus_hylocrius.JPG|Only 100 individuals of [[Nilgiri tahr]] were left in 2001 but recovered to 3,300 by 2010.\nFile:Nilgiri langur (1) by N. A. Naseer.jpg|The endemic [[Nilgiri langur]] is endangered.\n</gallery>\n\n===Reptiles===\nThe major population of the snake family [[Uropeltidae]] is restricted to the region.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Greene, H. W.  |author2=R. W. Mcdiarmid |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2005|title=Wallace and Savage: heroes, theories and venomous snake mimicry, Ecology and Evolution in the Tropics, a Herpetological Perspective|pages=190\u2013208|publisher=Chicago University of Chicago Press}}</ref> Several endemic reptile genera occur here, including the cane turtle [[Vijayachelys silvatica]], lizards like [[Salea]], [[Ristella]], [[Kaestlea]], snakes like [[Melanophidium]], [[Plectrurus]], [[Teretrurus]], [[Platyplectrurus]], [[Xylophis]], [[Rhabdops]] and so on. Species-level [[endemism]] is much higher and is common to almost all genera present here. Some enigmatic endemic reptiles include the venomous snakes such as the striped coral snake, the [[Malabar pit viper]], the [[large-scaled pitviper]] and the [[horseshoe pitviper]]. The region has a significant population of the vulnerable [[mugger crocodile]].<ref>{{citation|first=Andrews|last=Harry V.|title=Status and Distribution of the Mugger Crocodile in Tamil Nadu|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/crocodile/tnadu.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20041220055759/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/crocodile/tnadu.htm|archivedate=20 December 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Amphibians===\nThe [[amphibian]]s of the Western Ghats are diverse and unique, with more than 80% of the 179 amphibian species being endemic to the [[Tropical rainforests of India|rainforests]] of the mountains.<ref>{{citation|author=Vasudevan Karthikeyan|title=A Report on the Survey of Rainforest Fragments in the Western Ghats for Amphibian Diversity|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter19.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20051215224533/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter19.htm|archivedate=15 December 2005}}</ref> The endangered [[purple frog]] was discovered in 2003.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Radhakrishnan, C |author2=K.C. Gopi |author3=K.P. Dinesh  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2007| title=Zoogeography of ''Nasikabatrachus sahyadrensis'' Biju and Bossuyt (Amphibia: Anura; Nasikabatrachidae) in the Western Ghats, India|journal=Records of the Zoological Survey of India|volume=107|pages= 115\u2013121}}</ref> Several families of frogs, namely of the genera [[Micrixalus]], [[Indirana]], [[Nyctibatrachus]], are endemic to this region. Endemic genera include the toads [[Pedostibes]], [[Ghatophryne]], [[Xanthophryne]]; arboreal frogs such as [[Ghatixalus]], [[Mercurana]] and [[Beddomixalus]]; and microhylids like [[Melanobatrachus]]. New frog species were described from the Western Ghats in 2005, and more recently a new species, [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic]] of its genus [[Mysticellus]], was discovered.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2005/endemism_amphibian_summary_content.pdf|title=An evaluation of the endemism of the amphibian assemblages from the Western Ghats using molecular techniques|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219184326/http://www.wii.gov.in/publications/researchreports/2005/endemism_amphibian_summary_content.pdf|archivedate=19 December 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCmonotypic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-47208169|title=New 'mysterious' frog species discovered in India's Western Ghats|date=13 February 2019|work=BBC News}}</ref>\nThe region is also home to many [[Caecilians of the Western Ghats|caecilian species]].\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Marsh Crocodiles basking in the sun.JPG|The region has a significant population of the vulnerable [[mugger crocodile]].\nFile:Nasikabatrachus_sahyadrensis.jpg|The [[purple frog]] (''Nasikabatrachus sahyadrensis'') was discovered in 2003.\nFile:Rhacophorus_malabaricus_flat.jpg|The [[Rhacophorus|Malabar gliding frog]] is endemic to the Western Ghats.\nFile:Plectrurus_perottetti_sal.jpg|[[Uropeltidae|Pipe snakes]] are found only in South India and Sri Lanka.\nFile:Akwa18 puntius2.jpg|[[Denison's barb]] is threatened from habitat loss and is now bred in captivity.\n</gallery>\n\n===Fish===\n{{as of|2004}}, 288 freshwater fish species were listed for the Western Ghats, including 35 also known from [[brackish]] or marine water.<ref name=\"Neelesh Fish\"/> Several new species have been described from the region since then (e.g., ''[[Dario urops]]'' and ''[[Schistura sharavathiensis|S. sharavathiensis]]'').<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Britz|last2=Ali|last3=Philip|year=2012|title=Dariourops, a new species of badid fish from the Western Ghats, southern India|journal=Zootaxa|volume=3348|pages=63\u201368|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3348.1.5}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sreekantha|last2=Gururaja|last3=Remadevi|last4=Indra|last5=Ramachandra|year=2006|title=Two new species of the genus Schistura McClell and (Cypriniformes: Balitoridae) from western Ghats, India|journal=Zoos' Print Journal|volume=21|issue=4|pages=2211\u20132216|doi=10.11609/jott.zpj.1386.2211-6|doi-access=free}}</ref> There are 118 endemic species, including 13 genera entirely restricted to the Western Ghats (''[[Betadevario]]'', ''[[Day's round herring|Dayella]]'', ''[[Haludaria]]'', ''[[Horabagrus]]'', ''[[Horalabiosa]]'', ''[[Hypselobarbus]]'', ''[[Indoreonectes]]'', ''[[Lepidopygopsis]]'', ''[[Longischistura]]'', ''[[Mesonoemacheilus]]'', ''[[Parapsilorhynchus]]'', ''[[Rohtee]]'' and ''[[Travancoria]]'').<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal>{{cite book|author1=Molur, M. |author2=Smith, K.G. |author3=Daniel, B.A. |author4=Darwall, W.R.T.   |last-author-amp=yes |year=2011|url=https://portals.iucn.org/library/sites/library/files/documents/RL-540-001.pdf|title=The status and distribution of freshwater biodiversity in the Western Ghats, India|publisher=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species \u2013 Regional Assessment|isbn=978-2-8317-1381-6}}</ref>\n\nThere is a higher fish [[Species richness|richness]] in the southern part of the Western Ghats than in the northern,<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> and the highest is in the [[Chalakudy River]], which alone holds 98 species.<ref name=RaghavanFish>{{cite journal | last1 = Raghavan | last2 = Prasad | last3 = Ali | last4 = Pereira | year = 2008 | title = Fish fauna of Chalakudy River, part of Western Ghats biodiversity hotspot, Kerala, India: patterns of distribution, threats and conservation needs | url = | journal = Biodiversity and Conservation | volume = 17 | issue = 13| pages = 3119\u20133131 | doi=10.1007/s10531-007-9293-0}}</ref> Other rivers with high species numbers include the [[Periyar (river)|Periyar]], [[Bharatapuzha]], [[Pamba River|Pamba]] and [[Chaliyar]], as well as upstream tributaries of the [[Kaveri]], [[Pambar River (Kerala)|Pambar]], [[Bhavani River|Bhavani]] and [[Krishna River|Krishna]] rivers.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> The most species rich families are the [[Cyprinidae|Cyprinids]] (72 species), [[hillstream loach]]es (34 species; including [[Nemacheilidae|stone loaches]], now regarded a separate family), [[Bagridae|Bagrid catfishes]] (19 species) and [[Sisoridae|Sisorid catfishes]] (12 species).<ref name=\"Neelesh Fish\"/><ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/><ref name=RaghavanFish/> The region is home to several brilliantly coloured ornamental fishes like the [[Denison barb|Denison (or red line torpedo) barb]],<ref>Raghavan, R., Philip, S., Ali, A. & Dahanukar, N. (2013): [https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230040/http://www.threatenedtaxa.org/ZooPrintJournal/2013/November/o367326xi134932-4938.pdf ''Sahyadria'', a new genus of barbs (Teleostei: Cyprinidae) from Western Ghats of India.] ''Journal of Threatened Taxa'', 5 (15): 4932-4938.</ref> [[melon barb]], several species of ''[[Dawkinsia]]'' barbs, [[zebra loach]], ''Horabagrus'' catfish, [[dwarf pufferfish]] and [[Carinotetraodon imitator|dwarf Malabar pufferfish]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zoologica.lifescience.ntu.edu.tw/Z-10-1/Z-10-1-2.PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040716010207/http://zoologica.lifescience.ntu.edu.tw/Z-10-1/Z-10-1-2.PDF |url-status=dead |archive-date=16 July 2004 |title=Zoologica |access-date=18 December 2006 }}</ref> The rivers are also home to ''[[Osteobrama bakeri]]'', and larger species such as the [[Malabar snakehead]] and [[Tor malabaricus|Malabar mahseer]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Benziger | last2 = Philip | last3 = Raghavan | last4 = Ali | last5 = Sukumaran | last6 = Tharian | last7 = Dahanukar | last8 = Baby | last9 = Peter | last10 = Devi | last11 = Radhakrishnan | last12 = Haniffa | last13 = Britz | last14 = Antunes | year = 2011 | title = Unraveling a 146 Years Old Taxonomic Puzzle: Validation of Malabar Snakehead, Species-Status and Its Relevance for Channid Systematics and Evolution. | journal = PLOS One | volume = 6 | issue = 6| page = e21272 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0021272 | pmid=21731689 | pmc=3123301}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Silas | display-authors = etal   | year = 2005 | title = Indian Journal of Fisheries | volume = 52 | issue = 2| pages = 125\u2013140 }}</ref> A few are adapted to an [[Cavefish|underground life]], including some ''[[Monopterus]]'' swampeels,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gobi | first1 = K.C. | year = 2002 | title = A new synbranchid fish, Monopterus digressus from Kersla, Peninsular India | journal = Rec. Zool. Surv. India | volume = 100 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 137\u2013143 }}</ref> and the catfish ''[[Horaglanis]]'' and ''[[Kryptoglanis]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vincent | first1 = Moncey | last2 = Thomas | first2 = John | date = April 2011 | title = Kryptoglanis shajii, an enigmatic subterranean-spring catfish (Siluriformes, Incertae sedis) from Kerala, India | journal = Ichthyological Research | volume = 58 | issue = 2 | pages = 161\u2013165 | doi = 10.1007/s10228-011-0206-6 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[IUCN]], 97 freshwater fish species from the Western Ghats were considered [[Threatened species|threatened]] in 2011, including 12 critically endangered, 54 endangered and 31 vulnerable.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> All but one (''[[Tor khudree]]'') of these are endemic to the Western Ghats. An additional 26 species from the region are considered [[data deficient]] (their status is unclear at present). The primary threats are from [[habitat loss]], but also from [[overexploitation]] and [[introduced species]].<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/>\n\n===Birds===\nThere are at least 508 bird species. Most of Karnataka's five hundred species of birds are from the Western Ghats region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://karnatakabirds.net |title=Karnataka birds |publisher=karnatakabirds.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060429032225/http://www.karnatakabirds.net/ |archivedate=29 April 2006  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.karnatakaforest.gov.in/English/forest_glance/biodiversity.htm |title=Karnataka forest department (forests at a glance \u2013 Bio-diversity|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927093422/http://www.karnatakaforest.gov.in/English/forest_glance/biodiversity.htm|archive-date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> There are at least 16 species of birds endemic to the Western Ghats including the endangered [[rufous-breasted laughingthrush]], the vulnerable [[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]], [[white-bellied shortwing]] and [[broad-tailed grassbird]], the [[near threatened]] [[grey-breasted laughingthrush]], [[black-and-rufous flycatcher]], [[Nilgiri flycatcher]], and [[Nilgiri pipit]], and the [[least concern]] [[Blue-winged parakeet|Malabar (blue-winged) parakeet]], [[Malabar grey hornbill]], [[white-bellied treepie]], [[grey-headed bulbul]], [[rufous babbler]], [[Wayanad laughingthrush]], [[white-bellied blue-flycatcher]] and the [[crimson-backed sunbird]].<ref name=\"bli\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/ebas/index.html?action=EbaHTMDetails.asp&sid=125&m=0|title=Restricted-range species|year=1998|work=BirdLife EBA Factsheet 12 : Western Ghats|publisher=[[BirdLife International]]|access-date=3 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Columba elphinstonii.jpg|[[Nilgiri wood-pigeon]]\nFile:Great-Hornbill.jpg|[[Great hornbill]]\nFile:Crimson-fronted Barbet (Megalaima rubricapilla) - Male - Sakleshpur - India -2009.jpg|[[Malabar barbet]]\nFile:2005-malabar-parkeet-p.jpg|[[Blue-winged parakeet|Malabar (blue-winged) parakeet]]\nFile:NilgiriPipit.jpg|[[Nilgiri pipit]]\nFile:White bellied treepie Thattekad.jpg|[[White-bellied treepie]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Insects===\nThere are roughly 6,000 insect species.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Mathew George|author2=Binoy C.F.|lastauthoramp=yes|title=An Overview of Insect Diversity of Western Ghats with Special Reference to Kerala State|access-date=24 July 2007|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter3.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090316112850/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter3.htm|archivedate=16 March 2009}}</ref> Of 334 [[List of Western Ghats butterflies|Western Ghats butterfly]] species, 316 species have been reported from the [[Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve]].<ref>{{Citation|author1=George Mathew|author2=M. Mahesh Kumar|lastauthoramp=yes|title=State of the Art Knowledge on the Butterflies of Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter6.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090108105816/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter6.htm|archivedate=8 January 2009}}</ref> The Western Ghats are home to 174 species of [[odonates]] (107 [[dragonflies]] and 67 [[damselflies]]), including 69 endemics.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> Most of the endemic odonate are closely associated with rivers and streams, while the non-endemics typically are [[Generalist and specialist species|generalists]].<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/>\nThere are several species of [[leech]]es found all along the Western Ghats.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/069/01-04/0325-0328.pdf|title=Collection of leeches from Maharashtra|last=Chandra|first=Mahesh|year=1976|website=Zoological Survey of India|series=69 : 325\u2013328|publisher=Rec. Zool. Surv. India|access-date=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"140\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Malabar tree nymph 01.jpg|The [[Malabar tree nymph]] is endemic to the Western Ghats.\nFile:Tamil_Lacewing2_before.jpg|[[Cethosia nietneri|Tamil Lacewings]] are found only in South Asia.\nFile:Ischnura_heterosticta02.jpg|The Western Ghats have 67 species of [[damselflies]].\nFile:SnailWynaad.jpg|The endemic land snail ''[[Indrella ampulla]]''\nFile:Phallus Indusiatus2.jpg|''[[Phallus indusiatus]]'' found in the Western Ghats\n</gallery>\n\n===Molluscs===\nSeasonal rainfall patterns of the Western Ghats necessitate a period of [[diapause|dormancy]] for its [[land snail]]s, resulting in their high abundance and diversity including at least 258 species of [[gastropods]] from 57 genera and 24 families.<ref>{{Citation|author=Madhyastha N. A.|author2=Rajendra|author3=Mavinkurve G.|author4=Shanbhag Sandhya P.|last-author-amp=yes|title=Land Snails of Western Ghats|url=http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter9.htm|publisher=WII|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20090717093156/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter9.htm|archivedate=17 July 2009}}</ref> A total of 77 species of [[freshwater mollusc]]s (52 gastropods and 25 [[bivalves]]) have been recorded from the Western Ghats, but the actual number is likely higher.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> This include 28 endemics. Among the threatened freshwater molluscs are the mussels ''[[Pseudomulleria dalyi]]'', which is a [[Gondwana]]n relict, and the snail ''[[Cremnoconchus]]'', which is restricted to the spray zone of waterfalls.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/> According to the IUCN, 4 species of freshwater molluscs are considered endangered and 3 are vulnerable. An additional 19 species are considered data deficient.<ref name=IUCNAquaticAnimal/>\n\n==Flora==\nOf the 7,402 species of flowering plants occurring in the Western Ghats, 5,588 species are native or indigenous and 376 are exotics naturalised; 1,438 species are cultivated or planted as ornamentals. Among the indigenous species, 2,253 species are endemic to India and of them, 1,273 species are exclusively confined to the Western Ghats. Apart from 593 confirmed subspecies and varieties; 66 species, 5 subspecies and 14 varieties of doubtful occurrence are also reported, amounting to 8,080 taxa of flowering plants.<ref>Nayar, T.S., Rasiya Beegam A., and M. Sibi. (2014). Flowering Plants of the Western Ghats, India (2 Volumes), Jawaharlal Nehru Tropical Botanic Garden and Research Institute, Palode, Thiruvananthapuram, Kerala, India. p.1700</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghat Roads]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Mahajan, Harshal. ''A rendezvous with Sahyadri''\n* Ingalhalikar, Shrikant. ''Flowers of Sahyadri''. Corolla Publication; Pune\n* Wikramanayake, Eric; Eric Dinerstein; Colby J. Loucks; et al. (2002). ''Terrestrial Ecoregions of the Indo-Pacific: a Conservation Assessment.'' Island Press; Washington, DC.\n* Kapadia, Harish. ''Trek the Sahyadris''\n* [https://archive.is/20070228195706/http://www.wii.gov.in/envis/rain_forest/chapter2.htm Daniels, R.J. Ranjit, Wildlife institute of India, \"Biodiversity in the Western Ghats\"]\n* Ajith Kumar, [[S\u00e1lim Ali Centre for Ornithology and Natural History]], Coimbatore, India, Ravi Chellam, B.C.Choudhury, Divya Mudappa, Karthikeyan Vasudevan, N.M.Ishwar, Wildlife Institute of India, Dehra Dun, India, Barry Noon, Department of Fish and Wildlife Biology, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, U.S. (2002) \"''Impact of Rainforest Fragmentation on Small Mammals and Herpetofauna in the Western Ghats, South India''\", [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070701040125/http://www.wii.gov.in/faculty/publication/frag.wii.report.pdf Final Report, pp. 146, illus. Full text] retrieved 14 March 2007\n* Verma Desh Deepak (2002) \"''Thematic Report on Mountain Ecosystems''\", Ministry of Environment and Forests,13pp, retrieved 27 March 2007 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060618233452/http://biodiv.org/doc/world/in/in-nr-me-en.doc Thematic Report on Mountain Ecosystems] Full text, detailed data, not cited.\n* Abstracts, Edited by Lalitha Vijayan, Saconr. Vasudeva, University of Dharwad, Priyadarsanan, ATREE, Renee Borges, CES, ISSC, Jagdish Krishnaswamy, Atree & WCSP. Pramod, Sacon, Jagannatha Rao, R., FRLHTR. J. Ranjit Daniels, Care Earth, Compiled by S. Somasundaram, Sacon (1\u20132 December 2005) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130511231752/http://www.westernghatsforum.org/abstract_12_05.pdf ''Integrating Science and Management of Biodiversity in the Western Ghats''], 2nd National Conference of the Western Ghats Forum, Venue: State Forest Service College Coimbatore, Organized by [[S\u00e1lim Ali Centre for Ornithology and Natural History]], Anaikatty, Coimbatore \u2013 641108, India. Sponsored by Ministry of Environment and Forests, Government of India. Supported by The Arghyam Foundation, The Ford Foundation & Sir Dorabiji Trust Through Ashoka Trust for Research in Ecology and the Environment (ATREE)\n* [http://www.ces.iisc.ernet.in/biodiversity/sahyadri_enews/newsletter/issue30/M%20D%20S%20Chandran.pdf Shifting Cultivation, Sacred Groves and Conflicts in Colonial Forest Policy in the Western Ghats.] M.D. Subash Chandran; Chapter 22\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Western Ghats}}\n{{Sister project links}}\n{{wikivoyage}}\n* [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1342 Western Ghats], UNESCO World Heritage site\n* [http://wwf.panda.org/what_we_do/where_we_work/western_ghats/ Western Ghats], WWF\n{{Portal bar|India|Ecology}}\n{{GeoSouthAsia}}\n{{Western Ghats}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in India}}\n{{Mountain passes of India}}\n\n[[Category:Western Ghats| ]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of India]]\n[[Category:Physiographic provinces]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in India]]\n[[Category:Geography of Coimbatore]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Goa]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Mountains in Buddhism]]\n", "name_user": "Harinath Krishnamurthy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Ghats"}
{"title_page": "Lili Reinhart", "text_new": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lili Reinhart\n| image              = Lili Reinhart & Cole Sprouse (48478655701) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Reinhart at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = Lili Pauline Reinhart\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1996|9|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cleveland]], Ohio, U.S.<ref name=\"Editors\">{{cite web |url=https://www.biography.com/actor/lili-reinhart |website=Biography.com |title=Lili Reinhart Biography |date=June 26, 2018 |accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Lili Pauline Reinhart''' (born September 13, 1996) is an American actress, known for portraying [[Betty Cooper]] on [[The CW]] teen drama series'' [[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nReinhart was born in [[Cleveland]], Ohio, and raised in the nearby town of [[Bay Village, Ohio|Bay Village]].<ref name=\"Editors\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.avclub.com/lili-reinhart-and-camila-mendes-on-the-5-things-they-mi-1819440587 |title=Lili Reinhart and Camila Mendes on the 5 things they miss about their own Riverdales |last=Kaseko |first=Baraka |work=The A.V. Club |access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> She developed a love for singing, acting, and dancing at the age of 10, and begged her mom to drive her to [[New York City|New York]] for auditions.<ref name=\"Seventeen\" />\n\nReinhart moved to [[Los Angeles]] when she was 18 years old to pursue acting and almost gave up after five months.<ref name=\"Seventeen\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Acting ===\nReinhart guest starred on the television series ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' and starred in the television pilot for ''[[Scientastic!]]'' She also starred in the films ''Lilith'' (2011), ''[[Not Waving But Drowning (2012 film)|Not Waving But Drowning]]'' (2012), ''[[The Kings of Summer]]'' (2013), ''Gibsonburg'' (2013), ''[[Forever's End]]'' (2013), ''[[Miss Stevens]]'' (2016), and ''[[The Good Neighbor (film)|The Good Neighbor]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/who-plays-betty-veronica-on-riverdale-camila-mendes-lili-reinhart-will-be-your-new-favorite-duo-33226 |title=Who Plays Betty & Veronica On 'Riverdale'? Camila Mendes & Lili Reinhart Will Be Your New Favorite Duo |last=Kupfer |first=Lindsey |publisher=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=January 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 9, 2016, Reinhart was cast as [[Betty Cooper]], \"sweet, studious, eager-to-please and wholesome with a huge crush on her longtime best friend, [[Archie Andrews|Archie]]\" in [[The CW]]'s teen drama series ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]''.<ref name=\"Riverdale\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/riverdale-betty-cooper-lili-reinhart-jughead-jones-cole-sprouse-archie-comics-the-cw-pilot-1201699204/ |title='Riverdale' Archie Comics CW Pilot Casts Its Betty Cooper & Jughead Jones |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 9, 2016 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The series premiered on January 26, 2017, and is currently airing its fourth season. On January 7, 2020, [[The CW]] renewed the series for a fifth season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2020/01/07/the-cw-renewed-shows-2020-list-riverdale-flash/ |title=CW Renews Riverdale, Batwoman, Roswell, Black Lightning Plus 9 Others |last=Ausiello |first=Michael |work=TVLine |date=January 7, 2020 |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> Previously, Reinhart worked on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Surviving Jack]]''.<ref name=\"Cocked-Surviving Jack\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/surviving-jack-actress-lili-reinhart-joins-amazon-pilot-cocked-exclusive/ |title='Surviving Jack' Actress Lili Reinhart Joins Amazon Pilot 'Cocked' (Exclusive) |last=Sneider |first=Jeff |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmong her recent film roles, Reinhart starred in [[M\u00e9lanie Laurent]]'s ''[[Galveston (film)|Galveston]]'' (2018),<ref name=\"Galveston\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/02/riverdale-lili-reinhart-joins-galveston-movie-ben-foster-elle-fanning-nic-pizzolatto-1201908237/ |title='Riverdale's Lili Reinhart Joins Ben Foster & Elle Fanning In 'Galveston' |last=Patten |first=Dominic |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 10, 2017 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> and in [[Lorene Scafaria]]'s ''[[Hustlers (2019 film)|Hustlers]]'' (2019).<ref name=\"Hustlers\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/cardi-b-lili-reinhart-keke-palmer-julia-stiles-constance-wu-jennifer-lopez-hustlers-1202578260/ |title='Hustlers': Cardi B, Lili Reinhart, Keke Palmer & Julia Stiles Join Constance Wu & Jennifer Lopez In Avenging Strippers Pic |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Andreas |last=Wiseman |date=March 19, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Reinhart made a [[cameo appearance]] in [[Elizabeth Banks]]'s ''[[Charlie's Angels (2019 film)|Charlie's Angels]]'' (2019), as an Angel recruit.<ref name=\"CharliesAngelsArticle\" /><ref name=\"CharliesAngelsInstagram\" /> On June 14, 2019, it was announced that Reinhart would star as Grace Town in [[Richard Tanne]]'s upcoming film ''[[Chemical Hearts]]'' (2020).<ref name=\"ChemicalHearts\" /><ref name=\"Welk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-walking-dead-star-austin-abrams-joins-lili-reinharts-chemical-hearts-at-amazon/ |title='The Walking Dead' Star Austin Abrams Joins Lili Reinhart's 'Chemical Hearts' at Amazon |last=Welk |first=Brian |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=June 17, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> ''Chemical Hearts'' will be distributed by [[Amazon Studios]] and is Reinhart's first credit as an [[executive producer]] on a film.<ref name=\"ChemicalHearts\" /><ref name=\"Rearick\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3127619/lili-reinhart-executive-produce-amazon-movie-chemical-hearts/ |title=Lili Reinhart Will Executive Produce And Star In Your Next YA Obsesion |last=Rearick |first=Lauren |website=[[MTV News]] |date=June 14, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nOn October 8, 2019, it was announced that Reinhart will publish a book of poems called ''Swimming Lessons: Poems''.<ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/10/lili-reinhart-publish-book-of-poems-swimming-lessons.html |title=Lili Reinhart Will Publish a Book of Poems |last=Spellings |first=Sarah |website=The Cut |date=October 8, 2019 |accessdate=October 10, 2019}}</ref> Reinhart stated she decided she wanted to share her poetry with the world despite her fear of doing so and that her own experiences inspired the collection.<ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons-Instagram-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3XlejiA05q/ |title=One year ago, I decided I wanted to share my poetry with the world. It\u2019s scary to reveal a part of myself that I don\u2019t often show, but I like to consider this book as more of a story rather than a confession of thought. Strangers, songs, films, fictional characters, love in various forms, and of course my own experiences were my inspiration throughout the creation of Swimming Lessons. This book means a lot to me and I\u2019m very grateful to be in the position to finally share it \ud83c\udf37 pre-order link is in my bio if you\u2019re so inclined |last=Reinhart |first=Lili |work=Instagram |date=October 8, 2019 |accessdate=October 10, 2019}}</ref> The book explores young love and anxiety and depression in the face of fame.<ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons-Book-Description\">{{cite book |title=Swimming Lessons: Poems Paperback \u2013 May 5, 2020 |isbn=1250261759}}</ref> ''Swimming Lessons'' was originally scheduled to be released on May 5, 2020, but was delayed to September 29, 2020.<ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons\" /><ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons-Delayed-Instagram-Video\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-A-k3_gEY-/ |title=Book Release Update. Couldn\u2019t find a good cover pic for the video so here we are. Information about my book Swimming Lessons\u2019 new release date. Wishing you all happiness and health \u2764\ufe0f |last=Reinhart |first=Lili |website=Instagram |date=March 22, 2020 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons-Website\">{{cite web |url=https://static.macmillan.com/static/smp/swimming-lessons/ |title=Swimming Lessons Lili Reinhart Pre-Order Your Copy Now! |website=static.macmillan.com |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[InStyle]]'', Reinhart teased a possible sequel to ''Swimming Lessons'' by stating, \"Even as my book is ready to be published now, I'm already working on another. It's not like I'm even working on it, I'm just constantly writing and they're stacking up. Hopefully if my first book does well, I can keep going.\"<ref name=\"Lili-Reinhart-Swimming-Lessons-Sequel\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instyle.com/beauty/makeup/lili-reinhart-covergirl-interview |title=The $8 Mascara Lili Reinhart Uses for Her Betty Makeup on Riverdale |last=Lukas |first=Erin |website=InStyle |date=February 3, 2020 |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Partnerships===\nOn October 24, 2019, Reinhart announced that she partnered with [[American Express]] for the relaunch of its AmexGreen Card.<ref name=\"LRAmexGreenCardInstagram\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4Bgi_wg8t5/ |title=AmexGreen Card |work=Instagram |date=October 24, 2019 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LRAmexGreenCardArticle\">{{cite web |url=https://www.greenmatters.com/p/lili-reinhart-amex-green-card |title=Lili Reinhart's Advice for Empowering Youth: 'Stay Informed' |last=Hirsh |first=Sophie |website=GreenMatters |url-status=live |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Also in October 2019, Reinhart became a spokesperson and ambassador for [[CoverGirl]].<ref name=\"Covergirls\">{{cite web |url=https://www.covergirl.com/en_us/covergirls.html |title=Meet The Covergirls |work=CoverGirl |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LRNewFaceOfCoverGirlAllure\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allure.com/story/lili-reinhart-covergirl-ambassador |title=Lili Reinhart Is the New Face of CoverGirl |work=Allure |date=October 30, 2019 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LRNewFaceOfCoverGirlEliteDaily\">{{cite web |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/lili-reinhart-is-the-new-face-of-covergirl-she-looks-amazing-19279834 |title=Lili Reinhart Is The New Face Of CoverGirl, & She Looks Amazing |work=Elite Daily |date=October 30, 2019 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Erika Woods, CoverGirl's vice president of marketing, stated \"We're excited for Lili to join our family as she embodies a woman who is unapologetically herself \u2013 she is authentic, talented, and truly lives by what she believes in.\"<ref name=\"LRNewFaceOfCoverGirlAllure\" /><ref name=\"LRNewAmbassadorForCoverGirlElle\">{{cite web |url=https://www.elle.com/beauty/makeup-skin-care/a29637385/lili-reinhart-covergirl-ambassador/ |title=Lili Reinhart Is CoverGirl's Newest Ambassador |work=Elle |date=October 30, 2019 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nReinhart is very open about her struggles with [[depression (mood)|depression]] and says that ''Riverdale'' came into her life when she was in a very dark place.<ref name=\"Seventeen\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seventeen.com/about/a10392332/12-things-you-def-didnt-know-about-lili-reinhart-from-riverdale/ |title=Lili Reinhart Says \"Riverdale\" Helped Pull Her Out Of Her Depression |last1=Bennett |first1=Willa |last2=Fuentes |first2=Tamara |work=Seventeen |date=October 17, 2017 |accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!--TV movies go in with the 'Television' section as per WP:FILMOGRAPHY \u2013 do NOT add here -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''For Today''\n| Rachel\n| Short film\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| data-sort-value=\"Most Girl Part of You, The\" | ''The Most Girl Part of You''\n| Amy\n| Short film\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Lilith''\n| Lilith Wilson\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Not Waving But Drowning (2012 film)|Not Waving But Drowning]]''\n| Amy\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| data-sort-value=\"Kings of Summer, The\" | ''[[The Kings of Summer]]''\n| Vicki\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| data-sort-value=\"First Hope, The\" | ''The First Hope''\n| Karen\n| Short film\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Gibsonburg''\n| Kathy Colaner\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Forever's End]]''\n| Lily White\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Miss Stevens]]''\n| Margot Jensen\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| data-sort-value=\"Good Neighbor, The\" | ''[[The Good Neighbor (film)|The Good Neighbor]]''\n| Ashley\n| \n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Galveston (film)|Galveston]]''\n| Tiffany\n| \n| <ref name=\"Galveston\" />\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Hustlers (2019 film)|Hustlers]]''\n| Annabelle\n| \n| <ref name=\"Hustlers\" />\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Charlie's Angels (2019 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n| Angel recruit\n| Cameo appearance\n| <ref name=\"CharliesAngelsArticle\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3145092/lili-reinhart-charlies-angels-cameo/ |title=Lili Reinhart Will Make A Cameo In The ''Charlie's Angels'' Reboot \u2014 Because Girl Power! |work=MTV News |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CharliesAngelsInstagram\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4iYyJBg4U7/ |title=Charlie's Angels |work=Instagram |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Chemical Hearts]]''\n| Grace Town\n| Post-production; also executive producer\n| <ref name=\"ChemicalHearts\">{{cite we